<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tajik Refugees to Return Home From Turkmenistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 11 (Xinhua) -- A large number of Tajik
refugees will begin returning home from Turkmenistan next week,
the Interfax news agency reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This was announced in Dushanbe, capital of Turkmenistan, after
a meeting of the Tajik government, the Tajik National
Reconciliation Commission and the Office of the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
The International Organization for Migration has registered
2,500 Tajik refugees who would like to return home, the National
Reconciliation Commission spokesman Yusuf Khakimov said.
</P>
<P>
Over 300,000 people left Tajikistan for Turkmenistan at the end
of 1993 -- the greatest number of Tajik refugees living in any
other member nations of the Commonwealth of Independent States
(CIS).
</P>
<P>
The repatriation of Tajik refugees from Afghanistan has been
completed. However, only few refugees have returned from CIS
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
