<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Denounces Israeli Law on Census in East Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 11 (Xinhua) -- France on Thursday backed a plan
by Palestinians to make a census of the Arab population in East
Jerusalem and denounced an Israeli move to block the census.
</P>
<P>
The French position, made clear by Foreign Ministry spokeswoman
Anne Gazeau-Secret, was in response to a law adopted by the
Israeli parliament, or Knesset, to ban the population count.
</P>
<P>
"We consider that a law of circumstance voted in haste by the
Knesset to ban these operations is a new unilateral gesture
intending to impose a fait accompli," said Gazeau-Secret.
</P>
<P>
She recalled that the Israeli annexation of East Jerusalem in
the 1967 Middle East War has never been recognized by the world
community.
</P>
<P>
"The status of East Jerusalem will be fixed in terms of the
peace process. It is demanded of all sides not to do anything
which could jeopardize the existing status quo," she said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the planned census, "It is a good thing," the
spokeswoman said. "It is useful and legitimate to know the reality
of the demography of the Palestinian population in the territory."
</P>
<P>
The Knesset voted 23 for and 11 against in a rarely used
limited procedure on Wednesday to adopt the law banning the census
by Palestinians, at the demand of Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu to "preserve the Israeli sovereignty over Jerusalem."
</P>
<P>
It took place at the same time when thousands of Palestinian
agents began a nationwide census, the first of its kind in 30
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
