<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Recommends to Extend Mandate of UNFICYP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 11 (Xinhua) -- UN Secretary-General
Kofi Annan today recommended to extend the mandate of the United
Nations Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP) for another period
of six months until June 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
In his latest report to the Security Council, Annan said the
situation in Cyprus was calmer than in the preceding six months,
but the overall situation continued to be marked by tension.
</P>
<P>
He said he had appealed to both sides, as well as to Greece and
Turkey, to refrain form actions that could raise tension and
negative effect on efforts to achieve a peaceful settlement.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief said it was disappointing that after more than one
year of intensive discussion, the package of reciprocal measures
proposed by UNFICYP to reduce tension along the ceasefire lines
had still not been put in place, despite the Security Council's
repeated calls that the two sides should accept it without delay
or preconditions.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the presence of UNFICYP on the island remained
indispensable in order to maintain the ceasefire between the two
sides, which was a prerequisite for achieving the settlement of
the Cyprus question sought by the international community.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been virtually partitioned since 1974 when troops
from Turkey occupies the north of the island in response to coup
in Nicosia engineered by the military junta then ruling Greece.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Retail Sales Pick Up Slightly in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. retail sales in
November rose a lackluster 0.2 percent despite healthy growth at
clothing shops and furniture stores, the Commerce Department said
here today.
</P>
<P>
The disappointing monthly gains, to a seasonally adjusted 213.8
billion U.S. dollars, followed drops of 0.2 percent in October and
0.3 percent in September, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
In a separate report released today, the Labor Department said
new applications for unemployment benefits fell 13,000 to 311,000
last week after increasing by 20,000 during the last week of
November. Both figures were in the range economists say shows
strong demand for labor.
</P>
<P>
The lowest unemployment rate in 24 years has retained claims
low, and income gains outpacing inflation have supported retail
sales this year.
</P>
<P>
However, the retail sales in November were not quite as dismal
as portrayed in recent months from August to October. Besides,
November's sales were up 3.8 percent as compared with a year
earlier,.
</P>
<P>
But it was noticed that consumer spending has been shifting
recently from retail goods toward services such as travel because
ebbing demand for expensive appliances and electronic equipment.
</P>
<P>
Clothing and accessory stores reported an impressive
performance in November, with sales rising 1.2 percent. Furniture
and home furnishings sold well, too. Their sales jumped 1.3
percent. Both were the biggest increases in five months.
</P>
<P>
However, department store sales inched only 0.1 percent higher
and auto dealers' receipts increased just 0.2 percent after
sizable drops during the two previous months.
</P>
<P>
Sales of building materials, hardware and garden supplies fell
0.8 percent. Sales also declined at gas stations and restaurants
and bars.
</P>
<P>
Retail spending is regarded as a barometer of the country's
economic vigor. The U.S. consumers buy roughly two-thirds of the
nation's economic output and retail sales represents about half of
that. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
