<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Calls for Clear-cut Muslim Attitude Towards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
has called on the Muslim leaders to adopt a practical and
clear-cut attitude towards Israeli and the U.S. policies of
"tyranny oppression, exploitation and usurpation in the world."
</P>
<P>
This came in a message sent by the Iraqi president to the
on-going eighth summit of the Organization of Islamic Conference
here.
</P>
<P>
"Those (leaders) who represent the conscience of their peoples
should have such an attitude, which should be in deeds, not in
words," Saddam said in his message available to the summit today.
</P>
<P>
"Otherwise, the use of such meetings would remain a mere
reminding for those who forget that we are an Islamic nation, but
we are in fact far from Islam," he said.
</P>
<P>
Saddam himself did not show up at the summit and the Iraqi
delegation is led by Deputy Prime Minister Taha Yassin Ramadan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Meeting Calls For Protection of Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Representatives to a regional
meeting of the International Labor Organization today urged the
organization to make a strong response to minimize the adverse
effects of the current financial crisis in some Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
In a document entitled "Conclusions" adopted here today at the
end of the three-day 12th ILO Asian regional meeting, participants
called on the organization to take immediate steps on training and
redeployment of displaced workers and protection of women,
migrants and other groups which may be especially adversely
affected by the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The participants, including government ministers and officials,
employer and worker representatives from Asian countries and
regions, stressed that employment should be promoted through sound
enterprise development strategies, investment in human resources
and a business environment which is conducive to sustained
enterprise competitiveness in a rapidly-changing global economy.
</P>
<P>
The document said that despite economic progress, two-thirds of
the world's poor live in Asia. While some countries in the region
have experienced a prolonged period of exceptionally high economic
growth resulting in the reduction of the poverty, strong
employment growth and increased real wages, serious unemployment
and underemployment problems afflict many Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The document said, "poverty alleviation remains a major
challenge for many Asian countries. Unemployment and low returns
to labor lead to poverty. The Asian experience suggests that the
pace of poverty alleviation depends on the employment-intensity of
growth. Macroeconomic policies therefore need to ensure that
growth generates employment. National anti-poverty strategies,
established in consultation with the social partners, should be an
important feature of overall economic policies."
</P>
<P>
It said labor migration is currently associated with a number
of undesirable features such as clandestine and illegal migration,
unsatisfactory conditions of work and lack of protection for
migrant workers. Policies are needed in both sending and receiving
countries to deal effectively with regulation of labor flows and
protection of the rights of migrant workers.
</P>
<P>
The document also called on protection of the rights of women
and children.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Tightens Control Over Budget Funding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
Thursday signed a decree to ensure stable budget spending and cut
the debts of budget-financed organizations.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin signed the document at the Barvikha sanatorium near
Moscow, where he was receiving treatment on his acute respiratory
illness, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The decree would be submitted to the State Duma, the lower
house of parliament, for approval before March 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Under the administrative measure, an unspecified number of
federal organizations would close down and their administrators
would be responsible for sticking to spending limits.
</P>
<P>
The money thus saved would be used to fulfill the government's
obligations, but the decree did not say where the money would go.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the government would suggest cutting back on the
number of federal officials entitled to use communications and
transport means funded with tax-payer's money.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's latest move to tighten the belt on budget funding was
believed to be prompted by the International Monetary Fund's (IMF)
decision to suspend releasing big loans to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
The IMF, based in Washington, the United States, cited Russia's
inefficiency in tax collection and the federal government's wage
arrears as two of its reasons for the decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin Watches Modern Ballet Opera </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 11 (Xinhua) -- General Secretary of the
Central Committee of the Communist Party of China and President
Jiang Zemin watched the well-known modern ballet opera "Red
Detachment of Women", performed by the Central Ballet Troupe, in
Beijing this evening.
</P>
<P>
After the performance, Jiang, who is also Chairman of the
Central Military Commission, thanked the ballet dancers for their
successful show.
</P>
<P>
The opera tells the brave story of a group of young
revolutionary soldiers, most of them are women, in the Hainan
Island in south China, during the Communist Party-led
revolutionary war against the Kuomintang regime.
</P>
<P>
The Central Ballet Troupe was set up in 1959.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 2,000 servicemen watched the performance together with
members of the central military commission including its vice
chairmen Zhang Wannian and Chi Haotian. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
