<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IDB Finances Financial Sector Reform in Panama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American
Development Bank (IDB) today announced the approval of two loans
totaling 130.13 million U.S. dollars to back the sustained
development of Panama's financial sector.
</P>
<P>
The financing includes a fast-disbursing sector loan of some
120 million dollars equivalent designed to support reform of the
financial sector which will consists of important changes in the
legal framework, strengthening of the sector's mechanism for
safeguards and controls, and modernization of the public
development banks.
</P>
<P>
The loan will also be used to help strengthen the social
security system and assist in the creation of a debt securities
market.
</P>
<P>
Another loan of 10.13 million dollars will finance technical
cooperation to support the agencies in charge of financial reform
and supervision.
</P>
<P>
In a related program, the Multilateral Investment Fund (MIF),
an autonomous fund administered by the IDB, approved a 1.5 million
dollar grant to help strengthen Panama's Securities Commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ottawa to Let Provinces Design Their Own Tax Systems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Canada's federal government has
agreed to let the provinces design their own systems for personal
incomes taxes after years of refusal, a report said today.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Paul Martin agreed to a request from the
provinces that they be allowed more flexibility in setting rates
and tax brackets, according to the Globe and Mail newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The changes would allow the provinces to increase personal
exemptions or change the tax brackets for low or high-income
individuals as they see fit.
</P>
<P>
But Revenue Canada will continue to serve as the collector of
provincial personal income tax.
</P>
<P>
The new initiative, pushed by Manitoba, Saskatchewan, Alberta,
British Columbia and Newfoundland provinces, would likely to take
effect in year 2001, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 750 Killed in Traffic Accidents in October in France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Seven hundred and fifty people
were killed in traffic accidents in France in October, 1.6 percent
more than the same month last year, said road security officials
today.
</P>
<P>
The number of people killed in 12 months from last November
till the end of October stood at 7,990 people, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
The casualties from traffic accidents in France are among the
highest in industrialized countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
