<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Smart Card" to Clear Medical Bills in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 11 (Xinhua) -- American companies are
finding ways to speed up the clearance of medical bills. The
chip-embeded electronic card is one way to it.
</P>
<P>
The initiative by several technology companies -- including
MCI and Digital Equipment -- offers what is called "smart card,"
which looks like a credit card.
</P>
<P>
Insurers and managed care companies would give enrollees a
card containing their coverage information. The technology
consortium would lease computers and software to doctors,
hospitals and other health providers, according to a report of
the USA Today.
</P>
<P>
Payment processing would start with a swipe of the card in a
doctor's office. Patients would see what their insurance will pay
before leaving.
</P>
<P>
About 40 percent of the 3.7 billion medical bills issued each
year in the country are already processed electronically. Even so,
it said, insurers take an average of a month to pay. About 30
percent of claims must be refiled or reviewed.
</P>
<P>
The new service would not be available until March or April,
according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany to Raise VAT to Bail Out Pension System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The German parliament passed a
law Thursday to raise Germany's value added tax (VAT) to 16
percent from the current level of 15 percent in order to finance
the country's pension system.
</P>
<P>
Otherwise, pension contributions would have to increase to 21
percent of gross wages from the current level of 20.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The move could help prevent the cost of doing business in
Germany from running further higher for companies, which suffer
huge pension payment bill as the German population ages.
</P>
<P>
But the VAT increase has drawn protests from the German
retailers, who termed it as the "poison for consumption", killing
their hope for the coming year after five years of recession.
</P>
<P>
The VAT rise will take effect on April 1, 1998. It is noted
that however, the reduced VAT rate of seven percent for food and
essentials will remain unchanged.
</P>
<P>
"This is a good result," Norbert Bluem, the minister for social
affairs, thus commented the deal reached during overnight talks
between Chancellor Helmut Kohl's centre-right government and the
leftist opposition Social Democrats (SPD).
</P>
<P>
The SPD is capable of vetoing much of the government's domestic
legislation with the majority they enjoy in the upper house of the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The government and the SPD also agreed to slow down
liberalization of the German postal service.
</P>
<P>
Under an amended bill on post office privatization endorsed
today, the state-run post office will keep its monopoly on
delivery of letters weighing up to 200 grams and on mass mailings
in which individual letters weigh up to 50 grams for another five
years.
</P>
<P>
A regulatory agency will be set up to consider whether the post
office monopoly should be extended beyond the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the private firms will not be allowed to transport
mails, if their employees do not enjoy the full German social
welfare package.
</P>
<P>
Germany's Postal Customers Federation criticized the bill as
harming competition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Investigates Printing Paper Anti-Dumping Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 11 (Xinhua) -- China has officially decided
to investigate the illegal dumping of foreign printing papers
from the United States, Canada and the Republic of Korea on the
Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
The case, reportedly the first China has filed concerning the
dumping of foreign exports on the Chinese market, is designed to
use legal means to protect the rights and interests of relevant
domestic enterprises.
</P>
<P>
According to an announcement released today by the Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC), the investigation
will be carried out by the MOFTEC and the General Administration
of Customs in accordance with the regulations of the
People's Republic of China governing anti-dumping.
</P>
<P>
The State Economic and Trade Commission, in cooperation with
relevant State Council departments, will investigate the extent
of damage the dumping of the imported prining papers have caused
on the domestic industry.
</P>
<P>
The anti-dumping investigation involves printing papers
carrying specifications of 45 grams, 46 grams and 48.8 grams per
square meter and widths of 781 mm, 787 mm, 762 mm and 1562 mm. The
said papers carry the tariff number 48010000.
</P>
<P>
A MOFTEC spokesman said that China's anti-dumping
investigation will be carried out in strict accordance with
international standards.
</P>
<P>
He said the World Trade Organization has sanctioned
anti-dumping investigations and prosecutions as a legal means for
preventing unfair competition resulting from the dumping of
imports.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said China has adopted the following three
principles for conducting the investigation:
</P>
<P>
-- protecting the order of foreign trade and business and
opposing unfair trading activities in line with China's foreign
trade laws and regulations governing anti-dumping and
anti-subsidies;
</P>
<P>
-- preventing domestic industrial sectors from sustaining
damage resulting from the dumping of foreign products, and
protecting their legitimate rights and interests by using foreign
legislations and practices; and
</P>
<P>
-- adjudicating the case according to the facts and laws.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted that China will levy taxes in line with
anti-dumping and anti-subsidies regulations if the final results
of the investigation prove that the foreign printing paper was
illegally dumped and has caused damage to the Chinese domestic
industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
The MOFTEC and the State Economic and Trade Commission will offer
proposals according to the outcome of the anti-dumping
investigation. The anti-dumping tax will be determined by the State
Council and executed by the General Administration of Customs.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
