<HEADLINE> S. African Ruling Party to Maintain Current </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 11 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki said here today that the ruling African
National Congress (ANC) will maintain its current national
policy.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Mbeki said the forthcoming
50th ANC National Conference, due to be held from December 16 to
20, will be devoted to policy questions involving in all
important fields.
</P>
<P>
The issues to be discussed include the implementation of ANC
policies, social transformation, the orientation of development,
economic transformation, national peace and security, general
attractiveness of the ANC and the building of the party, and
international issues.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki confirmed that he has been nominated to succeed
President Nelson Mandela as ANC chief, but he expressed
disagreement to the saying that the leadership change indicated
"one (political) generation out and one generation in".
</P>
<P>
He noted that there will be no great change in the future ANC
leadership, and that "the current (ANC) policy will be
maintained," after Mandela gives up his chairmanship of the
party.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki also denied reports that the ANC leadership is deeply
involved in troubles because of different political viewpoints.
He said that the ANC always allowed different opinions within
the party, and it was in a very good state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
