<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Financial Sector's Contribution to UK Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 11 (Xinhua) - The economic contribution of the
UK financial sector has increased over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
Between 1986 and 1996, output of the financial sector increased
by 43 percent (3.6 percent per year), nearly double the overall
23 percent growth in the whole economy.
</P>
<P>
The sector makes an increasingly important contribution to the
UK economy accounting for 7 percent of GDP, Jeremy Seddon,
Director-General of British Invisibles (BI) told foreign
correspondents based here today.
</P>
<P>
Net overseas earnings of the the sector reached a record 22.7
billion pounds (36.32 billion US dollars) in 1996, 2 billion
pounds (3.2 billion US dollars) higher than in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Seddon said, the reduction in the current account deficit to
435 million pounds (696 million US dollars) in 1996 was more than
accounted for by an increase of 4.3 billion pounds (6.88 billion
US dollars) to 12.2 billion pounds (19.52 billion US dollars) in
the surplus on invisibles.
</P>
<P>
The financial sector encompasses banking, insurance and fund
management, venture capital, pension funds, unit and investment
trusts and derivatives.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the results, Duncan McKenzie, BI's Economic
Adviser said: "Financial services are increasingly important to
both the UK and world economy, and the UK is well positioned to
build on its present strengths." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
