<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European, US Multinationals Keep Their Faith in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Most European and US
multinational companies with business in Asia still maintain their
faith in the region after the recent currency turmoil there, the
Financial Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Citing a survey of 35 large multinationals by Renaissance
Technomic, a US management consultants, the newspaper said that 79
percent were not planning to change their strategy in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The survey of companies operating in Asia found that only about
15 percent felt significantly worse off because of the regional
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Some 14 percent foresaw stronger sales next year and the same
proportion expected increased rates of return. A small group felt
themselves in a stronger position post-crisis.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers with local factories felt the devalued currencies
offered opportunities to integrate their operations further
through the buyout of dealers or the purchase of greater stakes in
joint venture partners.
</P>
<P>
Exporters expected that the devalued currencies would lead to
increased shipments, offsetting tighter margins. 
</P>
</TEXT>
