<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein Leader Ends "Good" Meeting with Blair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams
said he had a good meeting with British Prime Minister Tony Blair
at the Downing Street early this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from the historic talks in Blair's residence, Adams
told reporters: "We had a good meeting because we engaged. I think
we faced up to the difficulties. In many ways the engagement can be
described as a moment in history."
</P>
<P>
He also said he looked forward to "a new relationship based on
ties of friendship" between him and the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, a reward to Sinn Fein for IRA's ceasefire in July,
was the first between a British prime minister and a Northern
Ireland Republican movement leader over the past 76 years.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein is the political wing of the Irish Republican Army
(IRA), the largest nationalist paramilitary organization in
Northern Ireland, which has been fighting to end the British rule
of the divided province over the past 28 years.
</P>
<P>
Before having the meeting with Blair, Adams said this morning
his goals at the meeting were to achieve a lasting peace in
Northern Ireland and a commitment from Blair that he would coax
pro-British Protestant Unionists towards a deal for the province.
</P>
<P>
The meeting has draw widespread criticism from Northern
Ireland's pro-British Protestant community, which fear the
government might agree to a united Ireland and an end of British
rule of Northern Ireland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
