<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OIC Summit Adopts Declaration to Condemn Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The eighth Islamic summit today
adopted Tehran Declaration to condemn Israeli occupation of
Palestinian and Arab lands, deploring the continuation of war in
Afghanistan and condemning all kinds of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The document, adopted at the concluding session after a
three-day debate, said that the leaders of 53 members of the
Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC) "condemn the continuing
occupation by Israel of Palestinian and other Arab territories
including Al-Qods (Jerusalem), the Syrian Golan (Heights) and
southern Lebanon."
</P>
<P>
The leaders saluted the steadfastness of the Palestinian,
Lebanese and Syrian peoples in their resistance to the Israeli
occupation, and called for the liberation of all occupied Arab
territories and restoration of the usurped rights of the
Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
They also condemned the expansionist policies and practices of
Israel, such as the establishment and expansion of Jewish
settlements in the occupied Palestinian territories, as well as
acts to change the demographic and geographic status of the Holy
City of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
They emphasized the need for Israel to desist from
state-terrorism which it continues to practice in utter disregard
for all legal and moral principles.
</P>
<P>
The participants called for making the Middle East a zone free
of nuclear weapons and other weapons of mass destruction, urging
Israel to join the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty and to put all
its nuclear installations under international safeguards.
</P>
<P>
They voiced support to the restoration of Palestinian rights of
self-determination and the establishment of an independent and
sovereign state with Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
The OIC leaders deplored the continuation of conflict and
violence in Afghanistan and expressed their full support for
inter-Afghan dialogs, formation of a broad-based government, and
activities at regional and international levels to stop the
bloodshed and establish lasting peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
They strongly condemned terrorism in all its forms and
manifestations while recognizing the rights of self-determination
of the peoples under colonial or alien domination or foreign
occupation.
</P>
<P>
They declared that the killing of innocent people is forbidden
in Islam, and reiterated their commitment to the provisions of the
OIC Code of Conduct for combating international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The leaders said that their countries are to intensify efforts
to conclude a treaty on combating terrorism, and called for
international cooperation in fight against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
They expressed their solidarity with the Muslims in Bosnia and
Herzegovina, and underscored their confidence that OIC's
Ministerial Contact Group will continue to actively pursue the
process of peace and reconstruction in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Tehran Declaration also called for rejection of the
aggression of Armenia against Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
It said that the OIC leaders called for complete withdrawal of
Armenian forces from all occupied territories.
</P>
<P>
They also called for the revival of Islamic civilization, which
should be in peaceful coexistence with other civilizations.
</P>
<P>
The leaders emphasized that the goal of the establishment of
Islamic common market constitutes a significant step towards
strengthening Islamic solidarity and enhancing the share of the
Islamic world in global trade.
</P>
<P>
The OIC invited member states to make a collective effort
towards substantial increase in trade and investment within the
Islamic world.
</P>
<P>
It urged them to consider the so-called D'Amato Law of the
United States, which blocks foreign companies to do business with
Iran and Libya, as null and void.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 leaders delivered speeches at the three-day summit
with the theme of "dignity, dialog and participation." It is the
biggest OIC event since the formation of the organization in
1970. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Israeli PM Supports Palestinian Statehood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Israel's former prime minister
Shimon Peres said here today that the Palestinians should have an
independent state, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Both the Jews and the Palestinians should have their own
independent states, and this will prevent clashes between the two
sides, Peres told reporters after a meeting with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the Israeli people support peace (with the
Palestinians)," and what they are divided over is "the price they
have to pay for peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
He asserted that the promise made by Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu to realize peace at the lowest cost has proven
wrong.
</P>
<P>
Peres arrived here this morning for a lightning visit, during
which he discussed with Mubarak chances for the success of the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said Egypt as a key player in bringing Palestinian and
Israeli viewpoints closer has always offered fresh ideas on
advancing the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Peres, now a Knesset (parliament) member from the opposition
Labor Party, said the need for peace inside Israel is very clear
and Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat has
done a lot in this respect.  
</P>
