<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Refugees Decrease in Last Three Years, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The African refugee
problem has been eased in the last two or three years,said the
visiting United Nations Assistant High Commissioner for Refugees
Sergio Vierira said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference at the UNHCR regional liaison
office here this evening, De Mello, who is also U.N.
Under-Secretary General for Humanitarian Affairs, said the number
of African refugees have decreased in recent years due to
repatiation plans in Mozambique and Zaire as well as the
repatriation of 2.3 million Rwandese refugees in 1994-1996.
</P>
<P>
Vierira disclosed that the UNHCR is operating in Liberia for the
repatriation of Liberian refugees which started in December 1997.
100,000 Burundi refugees will be repatriated soon and Sahel
refugees will be repatriated in 1998, he added.
</P>
<P>
But, he said, at the same time there remain very seriously
refugee problems in Somalia, Sudan, Sierra Leone and Angola. The
refugee problem in Angola has not been solved because of the
delay of implementation of the agreement of Lusaka, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the refugees situation in Ethiopia, De Mello said over
100,000 Ethiopians who took refuge in neighbouring countries have
returned home over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
He said that the repatriation of some 20,000 Ethiopian
refugees in neighbouring Sudan will be completed in May, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia is home to close 350,000 Somali and Sudanese
refugees, he said, adding that efforts are underway to repatriate
these refugees to their respective countries.
</P>
<P>
De Mello arrived here Tuesday. He has discussed with senior
Ethiopian government officials, and officials from the
Organizaiton of African Unity (OAU) and the United Nations
Economic Commission for Africa (ECA) on refugee and humanitarian
issues in Aafrica.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics issued by the UNHCR, at the January 1,
1997, Africa has 4,341,000 refugees and 2,058,000 internal
displaced people. The largest refugee producing African countries
are: Liberia-778,000, Somalia 572,000, Rwanda-467,000,
Sudan-464,000, Burundi-427,000, Sierra Leone-374,000 and
Eritrea-331,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
