<HEADLINE> Queen Says Goodbye to Royal Yacht Britannia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Queen Elizabeth bid
an emotional farewell to the Royal Yacht Britannia during a
ceremony at Portsmouth port in southern England today.
</P>
<P>
She appeared close to tears as the yacht's Royal Marines band
marked the official end of 44 years' service. Earlier the queen
toured the vessel accompanied by 13 other members of the Royal
family.
</P>
<P>
In a message to the ship's crew, she said: "It is with sadness
that we must now say goodbye to Britannia. We can all reflect with
pride and gratitude upon this great ship." The 6,000-ton ship has
ferried her all over the world.
</P>
<P>
Several members of the royal family wore naval uniforms for the
decommissioning ceremony, including the queen's husband Prince
Philip, her sons Prince Charles and Prince Andrew, and her
daughter Princess Anne. The Royal Marines band beat the retreat
playing "Rule Britannia".
</P>
<P>
The elegant Britannia has sailed more than one million sea
miles, the equivalent of more than 40 times round the world. Its
last major voyage was to Hong Kong at the end of June when Britain
transferred the sovereignty of Hong Kong back to China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
