<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-11 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Morocco: Islamic World Should Reconsider Ties With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Moroccan King Hassan II has
called upon those Islamic states which have embarked on the
establishment of relations with Israel to reconsider their stance
in the light of Israeli hardline policies towards peace.
</P>
<P>
This came in a written statement distributed today in the
conference hall of the eighth summit of the Organization of
Islamic Conference (OIC) in Iranian capital Tehran.
</P>
<P>
King Hassan II said these countries should do so until the
peace agreements and commitments reached by the concerned parties
are implemented.
</P>
<P>
The issue of holy Jerusalem and that of Palestine have always
been the focus of attention of the OIC, said the Moroccan king,
also the chairman of the seventh Islamic summit.
</P>
<P>
The OIC has been supporting the full rights of the Palestinian
people to establish their independent state on their national
territories with Jerusalem as its capital, he said.
</P>
<P>
It has also been supporting their struggle to practice their
political and national rights under the umbrella of just and
comprehensive peace on the basis of international legitimacy and
in line with the pledges and agreements approved in Madrid, Oslo
and Washington, he added.
</P>
<P>
"But the process has been stalled on all tracks as a result of
intransigence of the present Israeli government, completely
avoiding or abandoning its vowed commitments, and, instead,
proceeding to build settlements in the occupied Arab territories,
particularly in holy Jerusalem," said the king.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the OIC should adopt a decisive and
appropriate stance to challenge such intransigence obstructing the
activation of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He also called upon the international community to shoulder its
responsibility in siding against any measure that jeopardizes the
legitimate Arab and Islamic rights.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the economic dimension of Islamic solidarity,
King Hassan II said the OIC ought to give vital attention to the
economic dimension as an integral part of the organization's
efforts to create a mechanism that will prompt openness among
Islamic countries commercially and economically.
</P>
<P>
He further stated that such openness will always be one of the
strongest factors that prompt actual contacts and rapprochement,
and will create common interest among the OIC states, especially
in the existing global climate where economic blocs and
globalization are increasingly growing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
