<HEADLINE> Germany Backs Gradual EU Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Germany made clear Thursday that
it supports the European Commission design for a gradual
enlargement of the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
In a government statement made one day before the EU
enlargement summit in Luxembourg, Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
stressed the planned EU expansion should proceed "step by step" to
avoid putting too much strain on the Union.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission has proposed to start entry talks with
the five East European countries: Poland, Hungary, the Czech
Republic, Estonia, and Slovenia, as well as with Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The six other applicants: Bulgaria, Latvia, Lithuania, Romania,
Slovakia and Turkey, have been regarded not yet politically and
economically ready for admission talks.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel meanwhile stressed the expansion process should not lead
to new rifts in Europe.
</P>
<P>
"The signal from Luxembourg must be: All eleven candidates...
have a clear perspective of admission," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel also reiterated Bonn's position against including Turkey
in the first-wave membership negotiations, saying it has not yet
met the prerequisite for the talks.
</P>
<P>
Germany supports Turkey joining EU later, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
