<HEADLINE> EU Educational Program Receives Extra Funding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The European Parliament and
education ministers from the 15 EU countries have agreed to grant
a complementary 70 million ECUs (about 85 million U.S. dollars) to
Socrates, the EU's action program in the field of education.
</P>
<P>
The grant, which was approved Wednesday, will cover 1998 and
1999, the two years Socrates has left to run, the European
Commission, the EU's executive body, said in a press release
issued here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive said the decision followed the agreement the
ministers and the European Parliament reached on November 27
regarding the overall EU budget for 1998.
</P>
<P>
"It's a real Christmas present for all the schools and
universities, students, pupils and teachers who have worked so
hard to strengthen the European dimension in the education systems
of the 18 countries taking part in the program," said Ms. Edith
Cresson, EU commissioner for research, education and youth.
</P>
<P>
She added that education and training constituted a sector
which should receive priority attention "as a key instrument for
the future of the Union."
</P>
<P>
But she also said that the extra funding only amounted to an
increase of 20 percent per year compared with the current
situation. "It is by no means a luxury," said the commissioner,
adding that the total budget available was far from meeting
demand for participation in Socrates.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Socrates provided support for no less than 100,000
students, allowing them to spend time studying abroad in the EU,
and for nearly 10,000 schools participating in European
educational projects.
</P>
<P>
The Socrates also provided for some 40,000 young people
undertaking exchanges to improve language skills in the EU in the
year of 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
