<HEADLINE> Abidjan to Host First ECOWAS Tourism Fair Next </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) has decided to hold its first tourism and
leisure fair next April in Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at the 42nd session of the ECOWAS
Council of Ministers meeting that ended on Wednesday night in
Abuja, the Nigerian capital.
</P>
<P>
The ministers decided that the promotion of inter-regional
tourism would not only attract foreign exchange, but also hasten
regional integration, the News Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also decided that the second ECOWAS trade fair
would be hosted by Ghana in 1999, for which the ministers
approved a fund of 74,000 U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The ministers ended their meeting with a call on member
countries to ratify the protocol on community levy before the end
of this year.
</P>
<P>
The levy was agreed upon during the 19th ECOWAS summit of
heads of state in July 1996, as a solution to the community's
serious financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The protocol was expected to go into force early this year but
so far only Burkina Faso, Guinea and Togo have ratified it.
</P>
<P>
The meeting urged member countries to include the levy in
their 1998 budget, as was provided by the 20th ECOWAS summit of
heads of state in Abuja last August.
</P>
<P>
The ministers approved the establishment of a court of justice
which aggrieved member countries and citizens who feel their
rights have violated could resort to.
</P>
<P>
They also decided to revive the Committee of ECOWAS
Ambassadors so that the ambassadors can play a role in
facilitating contact with respective countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
