<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of taxi drivers of
Tel Aviv today staged a demonstration to protest the government's
plans to lower prices for taxi permits, causing massive traffic
jams in the city, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the demonstrating drivers blocked major
intersections of the city with their cars for several hours and
caused severe traffic disruptions.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Transportation Ministry decided early this month to
lower prices for taxi permit from 60,000 U.S. dollars to 56,000
dollars. Moreover, the sum for the permits is to be reduced
annually by five percent.
</P>
<P>
The ministry officials said that the change is intended to meet
the growing demand for taxis and ease the plight of passengers,
who often waste a great deal of time waiting for a taxi.
</P>
<P>
But Avraham Farid, chairman of the Association of Taxi
Drivers, contended that the change could result in doubling the
number of taxis on the road and would ruin the industry.
</P>
<P>
Farid said that if the demonstrations, which had been held in
Jerusalem Wednesday and will be held in Haifa Friday, have no
effect, the drivers would consider other measures, including a
taxi strike, next week. 
</P>
