<HEADLINE> Jordan's Parliament Denounces Iraq's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's House of
Representatives today issued a statement, strongly denouncing and
deploring the Monday execution of four Jordanian students by Iraq
on charge of smuggling car spare parts.
</P>
<P>
The statement was issued after the Jordanian government
ordered the expulsion of seven Iraqi diplomats Wednesday in
retaliation of the execution and made efforts to prevent Iraq from
executing the fifth Jordanian.
</P>
<P>
The statement denounced the execution as "inhuman and unjust,"
insisting that it constitutes "a flagrant violation" of
international legitimacy and human rights, official Radio Jordan
reported.
</P>
<P>
The execution also contradicted with the principles of good
neighborliness and brotherly ties, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
All the 80 members of the newly-elected House of
Representatives feel bewildered with the execution as it came at
a time when Jordan is making effort for the lifting of the United
Nations sanctions on Iraq, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Jawad Anani Wednesday summoned Iraqi
Ambassador Nouri Elwayess, telling him that seven of the
embassy's staff members should leave Amman in a week and urging
him to save the fifth Jordanian to be executed by Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jordan has recalled its charge d'affaires in
Baghdad Adel Sweidan back home for consultation. Other Jordanian
officials said that the government will adopt more actions later
at proper times.
</P>
<P>
Previous statements released by the government and the Senate
said it is an "unjust" decision to execute the Jordanians on
charge of smuggling auto spare parts worth only 620 Jordanian
dinars (878 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The statements insisted that the Jordanians should only be
punished with fine or prison term even if the charge is proved to
be true.
</P>
<P>
Semi-official Jordan Times today quoted an unnamed senior
government official as saying that the executed four were seized
in January 1996, released on bail in March this year, then called
back for trial in April and sentenced to death in September.
</P>
<P>
Car parts and many other goods are in short supply in Iraq,
which has been under U.N. sanctions since its 1990 invasion of
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
There are now over 100 Jordanian prisoners serving their
sentences in jails across Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Iraq used to be firm allies before and during the
1990-91 Gulf Crisis. But after that, bilateral ties suffered a
setback as Jordan distanced itself away from Iraq to end
international alienation.
</P>
<P>
However, the ties have been picking up in recent years as Iraq
began to provide the kingdom with more oil at discount prices and
kept increasing the volume of imports from Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is a main supplier of humanitarian goods for Baghdad
under the U.N.-Iraqi oil-for-food deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
