<HEADLINE> Clan Clashes Renewed in Somali Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, December 11 (Xinhua) -- After a day of calmness,
the Somali capital of Mogadishu was today once again caught in
bitter clashes between the country's two rival groups.
</P>
<P>
The fighting, which is still going on in north Mogadishu,
started in the densely populated area known as Manobolyo where
according to eyewitnesses widespread looting also occurred.
</P>
<P>
The eyewitnesses said the worst affected area is the main
Manobolyo market where several stores, shops and kiosks were
looted by angry militiamen. The eyewitnesses also said there has
been quite a number of civilian deaths in the market, but no
exact figure was available at this early stage of fighting.
</P>
<P>
Also, the residence of Ali Mahdi Mohamed, leader of the north
Mogadishu faction, has been under attack by one of the fighting
groups.
</P>
<P>
Ali Mahdi's security men belonging to one of the two rival
sides tried to defend the house in their last efforts. Ali
Mahdi's house seem to be isolated from all sides by rival
militiamen who blocked all roads leading to the house.
</P>
<P>
Houses belonging to well known and wealthy people have been
attacked and looted during the first stage of fighting early in
the afternoon and the militiamen also killed some of the
occupants, according to the eyewitnesses.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that the residence of Sheikh Sharif Sheikh
Mujhidin, north Mogadishu's former religious leader, was also
attacked in an attempt to reduce the pressure on Ali Mahdi's
residence.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of deaths were reported in north Mogadishu while
several vehicles including a land cruiser hired by the European
Union office in Mogadishu were looted. All streets in north
Mogadishu are now deserted with road blocks everywhere, except
some freelance looters who are busy collecting their booties in
the deserted business areas.
</P>
<P>
The fighting started at a time when a negotiation was
undergoing between the two groups who were fighting only a day
earlier in north Mogadishu, resulting in seven people killed.
</P>
<P>
Report said today's fighting broke out when four militiamen
kidnapped and shot dead one of the rival militiamen in Manobolyo
area, which angered the other side.
</P>
<P>
The clashes will further deteriorate the already poor security
situation in north Mogadishu, which has caused the evacuation of
several international aid agencies from the Somali capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
