<HEADLINE> Turkish Civil Servants Hold Strike for Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Turkish civil servants staged
a nationwide strike today against insufficient wages, the Anatolia
News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Police estimated that about half a million people took part in
the strike, which paralyzed urban traffic, closed schools and shut
markets and offices.
</P>
<P>
Some protest rallies were held in the major cities, but no
serious clashes have been reported.
</P>
<P>
Civil servants claimed that their wages are not enough to
support their families due to the high living expenses.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent decision by the government, civil
servants' wages will be increased by 30 percent in the first half
of next year when the annual inflation rate is estimated at 100
percent.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government, however, argues that rises of wages
would further stimulate the soaring inflation, making the
country's financial situation more difficult.
</P>
<P>
Today's strike was organized by the Confederation of Civil
Servants' Unions, which groups 1.8 million members throughout the
country.
</P>
<P>
The protesters said that they want to negotiate with the
government on the wage issue.
</P>
<P>
Most of the strikers will resume their work Friday but
railroad workers will stop their protest Saturday, organizers
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
