<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Concerned Over Demobilized Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 11 (Xinhua) -- SADC today expressed concern
over the increasing number of demobilized soldiers in the region,
saying they could become a source of instability if they are not
quickly integrated into society.
</P>
<P>
This was said by Kaire Mbuende, executive secretary of the
Southern Africa Development Community (SADC), when he briefed the
press here following a one-day SADC and European Union (EU) joint
committee meeting for senior officials, according to Zambia News
Agency ZANA.
</P>
<P>
Mbuende said a number of ex-war combatants could easily resort
to criminal activities for their livelihood if nothing is done to
integrate them into society.
</P>
<P>
A large number of soldiers in southern Africa have been
demobilized after the member states won independence in the 1980s
and peace process began in the past few years in some countries
that has long been beset by civil wars.
</P>
<P>
He said SADC will undertake an assessment to determine the
requirement of member states, especially Angola, Mozambique,
Zimbabwe and Namibia.
</P>
<P>
Mbuende called for external support in financial terms because
the amount of resources required for the program is beyond the
reach of the 14 member states.
</P>
<P>
During the news briefing, Mbuende lamented that there has been
a drop in the amount of aid flow to SADC with more emphasis being
placed on trade investment by the donor community.
</P>
<P>
He also urged EU to use its political influence to lobby for
debt reduction so that the region can concentrate its resources
on economic development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
