<HEADLINE> EU Sees Huge Rise in Info Services Trade: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)'s
total international transactions in communication, computer and
information services rose by nearly 160 percent to almost 26
billion ECUs (some 30 billion U.S. dollars) from 1985 to 1995, it
was learned here today.
</P>
<P>
The EU has been playing a key role in the burgeoning world
information society during the decade, said a report Thursday from
Eurostat, the EU's statistical office based in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
Development of computer and information services made a major
contribution to such an increase. The rise in this domain during
the decade was 352 percent to approximately 13.2 billion ECUs
(some 15 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Communication services were up 78 percent over the decade.
Eurostat noted that the growth might be substantially greater than
suggested by transactions in current prices, adding that the
average cost of international calls for an EU residential user
fell by 30 percent between 1993 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the 15 EU member nations represented 48 percent
of their total international transactions in communications and 54
percent in computer and information services.
</P>
<P>
The United States accounted for one fifth of the EU's trade in
communications and more than one quarter in computer and
information services.
</P>
<P>
"The technological boom in telecommunications...and development
of computer equipment have increased the accessibility of
international networks, thus creating greater opportunities for
international trade in computer and information services,"
Eurostat said in the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
