<HEADLINE> Strict Observation of Sanctions on S. Leone Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 11 (Xinhua) -- As the peace process in Sierra
Leone is in deadlock, ministers of west African states urged the
international community to ensure strict observation of the
sanctions and embargo imposed on Freetown's military regime.
</P>
<P>
It has become necessary to pursue the measure in view of the
failure of the regime to abide by the peace plan it entered last
October with the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS), said the ministers.
</P>
<P>
The ministers, who just ended the 42nd session of the ECOWAS
council of ministers Wednesday in the Nigerian capital Abuja,
noted that the regime led by Major Johnny Koroma had begun to
make new demands after signing the peace plan, the News Agency of
Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
Under the peace accord, the Koroma-led regime will hand over
power to ousted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah in April next year
and all combatants in the country will be disarmed, demobilized
and reintegrated between December 1 and 31 this year.
</P>
<P>
However, the ministers said, the implementation of the accord
had become problematic because Koroma was against disarming his
troops.
</P>
<P>
"He is demanding the immediate release of Foday Sankoh, who is
supposed to be released six months after the implementation of
the accord," they reportedly said.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh is the leader of the former rebel group Revolutionary
United Front, which has fought successive governments in Sierra
Leone and allied with Koroma's troops shortly after the May 25
coup.
</P>
<P>
The ministers noted there must be misunderstanding between
ECOWAS and Koroma and that agreed negotiation would have to take
place at the highest level later to resolve the misunderstanding.
</P>
<P>
A series of negotiations have been held between ECOWAS
delegates and those of the Koroma-led regime since the signing of
the peace accord in Conakry, Guinea.
</P>
<P>
The talks, however, failed to find modalities agreed upon by
both sides for the implementation of the Conakry peace accord.
</P>
<P>
The military regime is under economic sanctions and embargo of
arms and petroleum products imposed by ECOWAS and the United
Nations. 
</P>
