<HEADLINE> Gene Causing Allergies Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Washington, December 11 (Xinhua) -- A mutant gene that could
make people more susceptible to allergies has been tracked down by
researchers at the Washington University School of Medicine in St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
Experts said this finding, published in today's New England
Journal of Medicine, will be able to identify highly susceptible
people by looking for this gene and use it to tailor new
therapies.
</P>
<P>
Scientists have long noticed that allergies run in families,
and they believe that many genes, perhaps a dozen or more, are
involved in this common condition.
</P>
<P>
The researchers said their discovery implicates a gene that
controls a single step in th inflammatory process that leads to
asthma.
</P>
<P>
They said if you have this mutation, you are 10 times more
likely to be allergic.
</P>
<P>
Allergies begin when the body mistakes proteins from cat
dander, dust mites,cockroaches and other allergy producers for
dangerous invaders. A crucial step in the chain reaction that
follows is production of an antibody called IgE that causes
allergic reactions.
</P>
<P>
The gene that is mutated in some asthma victims contains the
building instruction for receptor for a chemical called
interleukin 4. This protein helps regulate the body's production
of IgE. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
