<HEADLINE> Donors Pledge 1 Billion US Dollars Aid to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Concluding a two-day
meeting here this afternoon, Tanzania's donors pledged some 1
billion U.S. Dollars aid to help the country meet its development
needs for the next year.
</P>
<P>
James Adams, the World Bank country director for Tanzania and
Uganda, told a press conference that participants agreed to
commit a total of some 1 billion U.S. Dollars to help meet
Tanzania's development needs in 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that donors would follow up closely
Tanzania's strategies in fighting corruption to ensure the
government funds are properly used.
</P>
<P>
Adams described as "a success" the Consultative Group Meeting
(CGM) for Tanzania which was attended by delegates from more than
30 countries in Europe, America and Asia as well as the
international organizations.
</P>
<P>
Several delegates showed their willingness to answer
Tanzania's appeal for setting up a fund to assist in reducing its
multilateral debt amounting to about half of its external debt of
8.1 billion U.S. Dollars by the end of October, he added.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Finance Minister Daniel Yona said at the joint press
conference at the Sheraton Hotel that his government was
committed to economy privatization but was at times seemingly
slow because the exercise has to be carried out carefully and
transparently.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting covered many issues, ranging from inflation,
corruption, privatization and debt to budget," he said. "The
donors seems to understand us better now."
</P>
<P>
Yona said that Tanzania would try to keep a balance between
development speed and governance transparency, explaining that
privatization means easing the government's burden in financing
some state-run enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"Some critics question us on speed, while others demand
transparency. We are trying to have both," he added.
</P>
<P>
CGM is a forum at which major donor countries and multilateral
institutions collectively meet, usually in Paris, individual
developing countries to review the donor-funded projects and
agree on future terms of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
This is the first donors' meeting ever held in Dar es Salaam
as a show of their confidence in the economic growth of the poor
East African nation.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania has scored good marks on macro-economic performance
with inflation rate declining to 15.8 percent this October from
25.1 percent in January of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Opening the meeting Wednesday, Tanzanian President Benjamin
Mkapa said Tanzania's debt was at a level that was both
unbearable and unsustainable, appealing for more debt relief and
setting up a multilateral debt fund.
</P>
<P>
"We currently spend on a per capita basis five times more
money to service only a part of our external debt than we can
afford for health and education combined," he said.
</P>
<P>
The donors are scheduled to meet Tanzania's representatives
from the business community and non-governmental organizations
before ending their three-day activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
