<HEADLINE> First Portuguese Dictionary Launched for African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Africa's first Portuguese
dictionary for primary school students was launched here today to
facilitate children in Portuguese-speaking countries to grasp the
self-teaching ability.
</P>
<P>
Fatima Beatriz, Angola's coordinator for the trial edition of
the dictionary, said today on the launching ceremony that this is
the first time for Africa's Portuguese-speaking countries to
utilize a unified dictionary in primary education.
</P>
<P>
The dictionary will help unifying education in Portuguese
language and bringing about a standardization in education, she
added.
</P>
<P>
In the five Portuguese-speaking countries which include
Angola, Mozambique, Guinea Bissau, Cape Verde and Sao Tome and
Principe, many primary and secondary school students cannot use
dictionaries, because they are beyond their level, and this has
seriously affected education.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the coordinator noted, the existing Portuguese
dictionaries are too advanced for primary education. She
believed that the new dictionary would help nurture kids'
interest in learning through dictionaries at an early stage.
</P>
<P>
The 288-page trial dictionary compiled by Aldomio Gomes, a
Portuguese professor and linguist, has included words for daily
use. Before the launch, the edition has been used in some primary
schools in Luanda and were well received by both teachers and
students. 
</P>
</TEXT>
