<HEADLINE> EU Threatens Legal Action Against Open Skies Deals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) will
be forced to take legal action again against EU members making
bilateral "open skies" aviation deals with the United States, a
top EU official said today.
</P>
<P>
Neil Kinnock, EU commissioner in charge of transport,
reportedly made the remark to EU transport ministers on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said that he would have to renew court action against EU
member states making such bilateral deals after the transport
ministers said they were not ready to give the EU's executive, the
European Commission, a wider mandate to negotiate an EU-U.S. deal
to liberalize aviation traffic.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive has been urging EU member countries to extend
its powers to negotiate with Washington to include the issues of
market access and traffic rights -- the right to fly to and inside
another country's territory.
</P>
<P>
The Commission added that Washington would not take interest in
a deal which did not include these issues.
</P>
<P>
A British diplomat was quoted by Reuters as saying that Britain
was not ready to decide on this matter before June 1998 at the
earliest. Britain will take over the EU's rotating presidency in
January, 1998.
</P>
<P>
It is feared among some EU transport ministers that EU-level
talks are likely to hinder their bilateral negotiations with the
U.S. since some EU members might seek more restrictive deals.
</P>
<P>
A total of eight EU countries, including Germany and the Nordic
states, have already signed such deals while there are ongoing
talks with four others -- Britain, France, Italy and Spain.
</P>
</TEXT>
