<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Why Kenya's Opposition Fails to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan opposition National
Development Party (NDP) leader Raila Odinga has ruled out the
possibility of fielding one opposition presidential candidate for
the December 29 general elections.
</P>
<P>
After presenting his nomination papers to vie for Langata
parliamentary seat Tuesday, Raila disclosed that despite
consultative meetings with opposition presidential candidates,
agreement had not been reached over the matter.
</P>
<P>
Consultations were held late last month among leaders in the
opposition parties to field one presidential candidate against
the incumbent President Daniel arap Moi, presidential candidate
for the ruling Kenya African National Union (KANU).
</P>
<P>
One day after presenting their nomination papers, opposition
presidential candidates Charity Ngilu for Social Democratic Party
and Kijana Wamalwa for Ford-Kenya were reported to meet on
December 4 in renewed efforts to field a single candidate.
</P>
<P>
These were the latest efforts made by opposition parties in
this east African country as a strategy to win the forthcoming
general elections.
</P>
<P>
The efforts to field a sole candidate against President Moi
was made as early as before the first multi-party elections in
1992.
</P>
<P>
But, the idea was not realized as the leaders of the then
mainstream opposition parties all felt strong enough to win the
elections.
</P>
<P>
As Moi was sworn in after winning the elections, there had
also been several attempts to unite the opposition leaders, but
neither materialized.
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, opposition parties in the country have
further divided during the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Take the Forum for the Restoration of Democracy (Ford) as
example. Soon after its founding, Ford gave birth to Ford-Kenya
and Ford Asili.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the opposition Ford has become grand parent
to Kenya National Congress (KNC) and Ford-People whose mother
party is Ford-Asili, and National Development Party of Kenya
(NDP) whose mother party is Ford-Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The repeated division of the original Ford indicated a tribal
inclination with Ford-Kenya and Ford-Asili being dominated by
Luyia tribe, NDP by Luo tribe, and Ford-People by Kikuyu tribe.
</P>
<P>
The current defections of the out-going opposition members of
parliament and their supporters are not a result of principles
but a way to get parliamentary seats through tribal backing.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are 28 registered opposition parties in
Kenya and almost every province in the country has a political
party whose leader and the presidential candidate comes from the
majority tribe.
</P>
<P>
Several years ago when the clamor for political pluralism was
at its climax, Moi predicted that sooner or later Kenya would be
characterized by ethnic-based political parties.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the ethnic divisions are the root
for the split in the opposition parties and tribalism has killed
their unity.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, communities in Kenya today believe that the
prime duty of a head of state is to feather his own nest or to
benefit his own tribe, and elections are meant to decide which
tribe will fete first.
</P>
<P>
Outgoing Imenti MP Kiraitu Murungi said in his book "Ethnicity
and Multi-Partyism in Kenya" that the Luos voted for a Luo
presidential candidate in 1992 because such a candidate was the
best placed to allocate national economic resources to Luos.
</P>
<P>
The Kikuyus voted for a Kikuyu presidential candidate for the
same reason, he added.
</P>
<P>
So, opposition presidential candidates and their ethnic-based
parties are vigorously searching for presidency and would not
surrender the opportunity for presidency to others.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, outgoing Lakipia West MP Dickson Kimani from
opposition Democratic Party of Kenya (DP) said recently, "Greed
for power among various opposition presidential candidates is
driving the entire opposition to the brink of death and nothing
much will be achieved by the end of the General Election."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
