<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Leaders Seeking Compromise on EMU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, December 12 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) leaders
Friday morning focused on issues of building a unified economic
system, so as find a compromise before moving on to other issues.
</P>
<P>
Officials were set to reach a deal on which the 15 EU member
countries should be allowed to join a proposed Euro council to
oversee the coming Economic and Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
The composition of the Euro council, mandated to discuss policy
issues under the EMU, became the main subject of discussion for
the EU leaders and finance ministers meeting here Friday.
</P>
<P>
They were expected to reach a compromise between EU members
likely to launch the EMU in January 1999 and those who intend to
stay out at that time -- Britain, Sweden, Denmark and Greece.
</P>
<P>
However, the four EMU "outs" still want to be associated with
the new system as closely as possible, as they do not want to be
left out in making the EU's future economic and monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
Ministers said Thursday they were optimistic that a compromise
might be found to make both parties happy.
</P>
<P>
"It would be strange if a compromise was not found on this
issue," Swedish Prime Minister Goran Persson said early Friday.
</P>
<P>
His optimism was also shared by some other EU ministers,
including Finnish Finance Minister Sauli Niinistoe and French
Finance Minister Dominique Strauss-Kahn.
</P>
<P>
Paris has been leading a drive for the so-called "Euro-x"
council, with the "x" to be filled in when the number of EMU
countries is finalized.
</P>
<P>
In the run-up to the EU summit, all EU members were optimistic
about finding a solution for non-EMU countries to associate
themselves with the Euro-x council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN to Strengthen Cooperation to Tackle HIV/AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Members of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) agreed here today to work together
more closely on HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
At a three-day annual meeting of the ASEAN Task Force on AIDS
(ATFOA), which ended today, representatives agreed that sharing of
the available expertise, information and experiences among ASEAN
national HIV/AIDS programs will help individual ASEAN member
countries make a stronger and more informed response to the AIDS
epidemic in the future.
</P>
<P>
The meeting adopted a plan of HIV/AIDS prevention and control
activities, which gives priority to the establishment of a
regional HIV/AIDS information and research exchange network.
</P>
<P>
The plan also calls on governments, non-governmental
organizations, the business sectors, communities and people to
cooperate more closely in response to the deadly epidemic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
