<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu to Present Albright Principles on Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu hopes to present U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright principles on the final settlement with the
Palestinians when they meet next week, a senior aide said today.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet Secretary Danny Naveh told Israel Radio that the
cabinet will discuss these principles on the further redeployment
in the West Bank and the final-status talks at Sunday's weekly
cabinet session.
</P>
<P>
He said the cabinet is expected to meet for the second time
before Netanyahu travels to Paris to meet with Albright, so
that Netanyahu could convey to Albright the principles on the
second redeployment in the West Bank and the permanent talks.
</P>
<P>
Before the cabinet debate on the final map, Israeli Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and National Infrastructure Minister
Ariel Sharon took a flight today over the West Bank to inspect
what areas should remain under Israeli control in the final
settlement to meet its security needs.
</P>
<P>
Late Thursday, the ministerial panel in charge of drawing the
final map on the redeployments and permanent talks held its fourth
meeting, but still failed to produce an agreement due to inner
split over Israel's security needs. The committee is headed by
Netanyahu and includes Mordechai, Sharon and Foreign Minister
David Levy.
</P>
<P>
Albright hopes to learn about the specific percentage rather
than only principles, and she has made it clear that Israel
must make a concrete and more credible decision on the second
pullback.
</P>
<P>
Both Mordechai and Sharon denied an Israel Radio report
Thursday that the government is to approve handing over 13
percent of the West Bank in the second redeployment. The report
said the map was drawn up by Mordechai and Sharon through secret
consultations.
</P>
<P>
Levy issued an urgent call to the government Thursday to
produce an agreement on the final map before the
Netanyahu-Albright meeting. He warned that failure to do so
would anger the Americans, harming the friendship with the
United States and leading to further international isolation.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government is growing impatient with Israel's
handling of the Israeli-Palestinian peace process, especially the
delays in the first two of three-phase further redeployments in
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
While the Israeli government is striving to produce a final
map, U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Martin Indyk, who retired
as U.S. Ambassador to Israel earlier this year, is scheduled to
arrive in Israel today. Indyk is expected to prod Israeli
cabinet to come up soon with a final agreement on further
redeployment and final settlement.
</P>
<P>
Indyk will also explore ways of breaking the protracted
deadlock in the peace talks between Israel and Syria. After his
visits to Israel and the Palestinian National Authority, he is to
visit Syria and Jordan before joining Albright in her meeting
with Netanyahu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of Canada Raises Bank Rate to 4.50 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Canada raised its
bank rate by 50 basis points Friday to 4.50 percent.
</P>
<P>
The bank's operating band for the overnight rate was similarly
adjusted.
</P>
<P>
The raise immediately boosted the sagging Canadian dollar to
0.7075 U.S. dollars, which fell to 0.6998 U.S. dollars on
Thursday, the lowest in 11 years.
</P>
<P>
"Volatility in international financial markets, tied to events in
Asia, has continued to affect Canadian markets," the bank said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
"This action by the Bank is designed to contribute to more
settled domestic markets in which investors can focus more
confidently on the strong fundamentals favoring non-inflationary
growth in the Canadian economy," it said.
</P>
<P>
Friday's move was the fourth hike this year by Canada's central
bank. It last raised interest rates by 25 basis points on November
25.
</P>
<P>
The bank has been reluctant to raise interest rates, fearing that
higher rates would stall Canada's economy growth.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the sagging Canadian dollar finally forced it to take the
difficult action. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Banks Raise Prime Rates to 6.0 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Canada's commercial banks
announced Friday the increase of prime lending rate to 6.0 percent
from 5.50 percent.
</P>
<P>
The new rates will be effective Monday, the banks said.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce took the lead in raising its
prime rate after the Bank of Canada jerked its bank rate by 50 basis
points to 4.50 percent Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
The move was followed immediately by the Royal Bank, Scotiabank,
the Bank of Montreal, Toronto Dominian Bank and other commercial
banks.
</P>
<P>
The central bank raised its bank rate after the Canadian dollar
hit a 11-year low at Thursday's markets.
</P>
<P>
The raise immediately boosted the sagging Canadian dollar to
0.7075 U.S. dollars today, which closed at 70.08 U.S. cents on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Friday's rate increase was the fourth hike this year by
Canada's central bank. It last raised interest rates by 25 basis
points on November 25.
</P>
<P>
The bank has been reluctant to raise interest rates, fearing
that higher rates would stall Canada's economy growth.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the sagging Canadian dollar finally forced it to make the
difficult decision of rate hike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
