<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Six Chosen as Final Nagano Olympic Torch Runners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 12 (Xinhua) -- A British anti-lanmine activist,
two runners and three Olympic Nordic combined champions have been
chosen as the final torch runners at the opening ceremony of the
Nagano Olympic Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
According to Kyodo reports on Friday, mine activist Chris Moon
and Japanese female runners Hiromi Suzuki and Masako Chiba will be
among the final torch bearers.
</P>
<P>
Kyodo reported that chief ceremony producer Keita Asari also
picked Takanori Kono, Masashi Abe and Reiichi Mikata - all
gold-medal winners for Japan in the Olympic Nordic combined team
event - to round out the six-member team at the February 7
ceremony at Nagano.
</P>
<P>
Midori Ito, the former Olympic figure skating medalist, will
light the cauldron at the Olympic stadium.
</P>
<P>
A former British army officer, Moon lost a leg and an arm while
defusing land mines in Mozambique in 1995. He will join the
opening ceremony with the use of leg and hand prosthetics.
</P>
<P>
After the Olympic flame is lit in Greece on December 19, the
torch will travel through all of Japan's 47 prefectures from
January 6 to February 7. About 1,200 runners are involved in the
monthlong nationwide torch relay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
