<HEADLINE> Chernomyrdin Lays Wreath at Unknown Tomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin Friday laid a wreath at the Tomb of the Unknown
Soldiers near the Kremlin, after the Honor Guard No.1 was revived
at the Eternal Flames by the tomb, the Itar-Tass reported.
</P>
<P>
"This is our duty to immortalize the memory of all those who
gave their lives to defend our country during the Great Patriotic
War, 1941-1945," Chernomyrdin said.
</P>
<P>
The Honor Guard No.1 at the Lenin Mausoleum was instituted in
January 1924 on the eve of Lenin's funeral. "The Leninist guard of
honour" stood till the 1993 October incident when it was disbanded
by President Boris Yeltsin after he put down an armed rebellion by
the former parliament.
</P>
<P>
The duty was revived in accordance with a decree signed by
President Yeltsin three days ago.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers of the presidential regiment will be on the guard Post
from 8 a.m. to 8 p.m. ever from this Friday, Russia's Constitution
Day holiday, which celebrates the passage of a post-Soviet
constitution on December 12, 1993. 
</P>
