<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Confident of Peso Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 12 (Xinhua) -- President Fidel Ramos today
expressed confidence that the Philippines can withstand the
fallout of the latest currency crisis that hit South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine peso dipped to a new record low of 37.3 pesos to
the U.S. dollar at the close of trading today after piercing
through a new psychological level of 36 pesos to one dollar
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The peso has so far lost more than 41 percent in its value
against the dollar since its floating in July this year.
</P>
<P>
But Ramos said the behavior of the peso can be traced to the
collapse of the Korean won which has depreciated by as much as 102
percent against the dollar since January this year.
</P>
<P>
The behavior of the foreign currency market is a daily thing
and one must not be apprehensive about what is happening outside.
We are affected but we have the chance to recover, he said.
</P>
<P>
Compared with other Southeast Asian currencies, Ramos said the
performance of the peso this month is better due to the sound
economical fundamentals of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines is about to graduate from the supervision of
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) at a time when other "tiger"
economies in the region like South Korea and Thailand have
re-entered into the IMF fold, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
