<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Rejects EU Invitation to Weekend Dinner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has turned down the
invitation for its top government official to dine with European
Union (EU) leaders at the weekend in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's frustrated move, sources here said Friday, was due to
the EU's reluctance to include Ankara in its initial blueprint for
enlargement, somehow on political reasons.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Jean-Claude Juncker, Luxembourg's prime minister, was
quoted by BBC World Service as saying that Turkey would not be
invited to a new European Conference of all other 11 EU applicants.
</P>
<P>
Juncker said Turkey would have to improve its human rights
record, relations with neighboring Greece and readiness to allow
EU entry negotiations with Cyprus to go ahead in the first place.
</P>
<P>
Turkey "is on the way to being a member, but we do have some
problems with the human rights situation," he told BBC.
</P>
<P>
However, EU Commissioner Han van den Broek said it was
"premature" to draw political conclusions from Ankara's refusal to
attend the dinner, which he described as "lack of a political
appetite."
</P>
<P>
Some EU members worried that a frustrated Turkey might push
Ankara into the arms of radical Islam while some others said that
it was simply a diplomatic move.
</P>
<P>
"It's not a disaster, but it's a missed chance. I'm not very
happy about that," Belgian Prime Minister Erik Derycke said.
</P>
<P>
The Luxembourg summit is expected to reach agreement on
starting entry talks early next year with the five-plus-one
configuration recommended by the European Commission in July --
Poland, Hungary, the Czech Republic, Estonia, Slovenia and Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The other five applicants -- Romania, Bulgaria, Latvia,
Lithuania and Slovakia -- are considered less qualified for EU
membership. They are likely to be involved in a "screening"
process launched by the EU to keep them going for further
political and economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
The EU leaders are expected at the summit to discuss EU
enlargement, a single European currency system, the Structural
Funds, agricultural and institutional reforms, and issues which
they have long been engaged with. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
