<HEADLINE> Danish Bio-Tech Company Sets Up Beijing Research Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 12, (Xinhua) -- Novo Nordisk, the largest
bio-tech company in Denmark, opened a new biotechnology research
and development center in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
The center, constructed at a cost of ten million US dollars,
includes a biotechnology laboratory and an enzyme applications
laboratory. It will make researches on biological products and
industrial enzymes.
</P>
<P>
The biotechnology laboratory will develop new products,
including a new industrial enzyme which can be produced in China
and which is suitable for China's current industrial
development. The applications laboratory will provide services for
enzyme applications.
</P>
<P>
The company president said the facility will help promote the
researches and applications of biotechnology in China.
</P>
<P>
He said the company hopes to establish wide-ranging
relations with Chinese universities and institutes.
</P>
<P>
Present at the opening ceremony were Wang Guangying, vice
chairman of the National People's Congress Standing Committee,
Peng Yu, vice minister of Public Health, and Christopher Bramsen,
Danish Ambassador to China.
</P>
<P>
Novo Nordisk, one of the world's leading producers of
industrial enzymes, is the largest Danish company in China. It
leads the world in the production of insulin used for the
treatment of diabetes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
