sank to a new low, closing at 45.65 to the U.S. dollar, according
to local TV Channel 7.
</P>
<P>
The baht has lost 77 percent of its value against the dollar
since the baht was floated on July 2.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the baht dropped to 43.60 per dollar.
</P>
<P>
Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai today held the tumbling South
Korean won responsible for the plunge of the baht to an all-time
low.
</P>
<P>
Chaiyawat Wibulswasdi, governor of the Bank of Thailand, said
the baht had further fallen because of the huge demand by Thai
companies to buy dollars to repay their debts before the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
Dealers predicted that the baht could decline further next week
if the Korean won continues to tumble.  
