<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, U.S. Urged to Reduce Greenhouse Gas Emissions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 12 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) countries
and the United States should take a lead in reducing greenhouse
gas emissions, Zimbabwe's Mines, Environment and Tourism Minister
Simon Khaya Moyo said today.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the appeal when addressing journalists in
Harare soon after his return from the third conference of parties
to the climate change in Kyoto, Japan.
</P>
<P>
Moyo said since the convention came into force in 1994, little
progress had been made towards implementation of commitments by
developed countries towards the reduction of emissions of
greenhouse gases to 1990 levels by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
He said some countries were "ridiculously" proposing the same
targets to be accomplished between year 2008 and 2012.
</P>
<P>
"If we are serious in resolving the issue of climate change,
we need to come up with more responsible and realistic targets,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
A protocol which was finally adopted by the conference calls
for a 5.2 percentage reduction of emissions from developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
Specifically the EU will reduce its emissions by eight
percent, the U.S. by seven percent, and Japan by six percent of
the 1990 levels between 2008 and 2012.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries are exempted from the new commitments to
the mitigation of global warming.
</P>
<P>
Moyo said there was need for differentiation of
responsibilities so that while developed countries should
concentrate on reduction, limitation and mitigation measures,
developing countries needed to focus on sustained economic growth
and adaptation measures.
</P>
<P>
He said developed countries should assist in the
implementation of the convention through the transfer of
environmentally sound technologies and financial resources.
</P>
<P>
He said Zimbabwe still needed to develop a national plan on
greenhouse gas abatement, limitation and adaptation measures.
</P>
<P>
"We will therefore need assistance in terms of capacity
building and financial resources in order to achieve this goal,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
