<HEADLINE> King Sihanouk to Pardon Deposed Prince: Sam Rainsy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's King Norodom
Sihanouk agreed on Friday to pardon exiled First Prime Minister
Norodom Ranariddh if the latter was convicted by a court, former
finance minister Sam Rainsy said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here viewed it as a move, on the king's part, to
eliminate a major hurdle to Ranariddh's return for general
elections scheduled for May 1998.
</P>
<P>
Sam Rainsy, president of the Khmer Nation Party, told the press
after meeting the king that the monarch would pardon his son even
if there was no such request from the prince himself or from
Second Prime Minister Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
However, the prince said he was not guilty at all and would not
sit in court.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh was ousted in July by Hun Sen, who accused the prince
of illegally importing weapons and colluding with the outlawed
Khmer Rouge and insisted he be tried by court.
</P>
<P>
If convicted, the prince would have to be pardoned by his
75-year-old father to join the elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
