<HEADLINE> Foreign Grant for China's Health Programs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Ministry of Health
recently received a grant of one million US dollars from the
US-based Bristol-Myers Squibb Foundation to fund three health care
programs over the next four years.
</P>
<P>
The programs will provide training, education and information
transfers for Chinese health professionals. The programs will
focus on the prevention of cardiovascular diseases, nutrition,
food safety and modern health care management.
</P>
<P>
The cardiovascular disease prevention program will include a
training course for some 7,500 medical professionals, and a
national epidemiological research program on cardiovascular
diseases.
</P>
<P>
The nutrition and food safety program will provide hundreds of
nutritionists and food safety workers with training related to
nutrition aspects for preventing chronic diseases amongst special
groups, including children, pregnant women and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the modern health care management program is to
upgrade the management skills of health care policy-makers and
directors of hospitals, educational institutions and research
centers.
</P>
<P>
The Bristol-Myers Squibb Foundation is a philanthropic branch
of Bristol-Myers Squibb, a global pharmaceutical and health care
company which has manufactured more than 30 kinds of products in
China since 1982. 
</P>
</TEXT>
