<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Leads Omega PGA Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 12 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's Choi Kyung-ju
made the most of the early morning's calm conditions to fire his
second successive five-under-par 65 to take the lead after the
second round of the 500,000 U.S. dollars Omega PGA Championship
here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 27-year-old, number one at the South Korean PGA Tour for
the past two years, leads on 10 under par by five strokes from
Hong Kong's Dominique Boulet, Myanmar's Zaw Moe, Scotland's Kenny
Walker, Singapore's Dino Kwek and Lu Wen-teh from Chinese Taipei.
</P>
<P>
In what is the final strokeplay event of the 1997 Omega Tour,
Choi started the day a stroke behind first round leader and close
friend Park No-seok but took charge by firing seven birdies and
two bogies.
</P>
<P>
Park, who represented South Korea with Choi at this year's
Alfred Dunhill Cup and World Cup, fell off the pace with a
two-over-par 72 to lie at four under for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
Choi's round, in chilly weather which saw winds strengthen in
the afternoon, was highlighted by a brilliant front nine of
four-under-par 31 with birdies on one, two, seven and nine.
</P>
<P>
"I was really concentrating," said Choi, who trained as a
powerlifter as a teenager. "I was unlucky with some bad lies but
I played very well. On the greens I felt like I could hole
anything,"
</P>
<P>
The South Korean continued to charge up the leaderboard with
birdies on 10, 11 and 14 before the wheels came off with
disappointing dropped shots on 15 and 18, both par fives.
</P>
<P>
"My poor finish reminded me of the Dubai Creek Open last year.
Everything was going well and then suddenly things started to go
very wrong," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I couldn't do anything to stop the dropped shots," he added.
</P>
<P>
Choi, leader by three strokes after three rounds in the Dubai
tournament, struggled on the final day finishing tied fourth.
</P>
<P>
Choi is hungry for a maiden win on the Omega Tour having
enjoyed an outstanding season in South Korea, with three victories
 in the space of five weeks.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's Boulet moved into contention after carding a
one-under-par 69, while Moe, winner of this year's Singapore Open,
Lu, Walker and Kwek returned 69,71,67 and 69 respectively.
</P>
<P>
American Mike Cunning put his Omega Order of Merit title
chances in jeopardy after missing the cut for the first time in
the Omega Tour's three years history.
</P>
<P>
Cunning, leader of the Omega Order of Merit fired a
four-over-par 74 to finish on four-over-par 69 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Of the players who could catch him winning the title, Canadian
Jim Rutledge is the best placed. Rutledge is two under for the
tournament after carding a two-under-par 68.
</P>
<P>
And among others were India's Jeev Milhka Singh, two over for
the tournament, and Americans Ted Purdy and Gerry Norquist, both
one under. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
