<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets Fijian Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng today
expressed his hope that Fiji will properly address various issues
affecting the Sino-Fijian ties so as to ensure that bilateral
relations proceed in a stable manner.
</P>
<P>
Li made the remarks during a meeting here with visiting Fijian
Minister of Foreign Affairs and Trade Berenado Vunibobo.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that Fiji is an important nation in the South-Pacific
Region and said the Chinese government attaches great importance
to its ties with that country.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-Fijian relations have been good as a whole and the two
countries have conducted frequent contacts since they established
diplomatic ties, said Li.
</P>
<P>
He also noted the broad prospects for the further development
of the Sino-Fujian ties so long as the two sides strictly abide by
the principles set forth in the communique on the establishment of
bilateral diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
Vunibobo told Li that the Fijian government highly values its
ties with China and appreciates China for its aid, which he said
has played a positive role in his nation's construction.
</P>
<P>
Overseas Chinese living in Fiji have made contributions to that
country's social and economic development, according to Vunibobo.
</P>
<P>
Vunibobo emphasized that the Fijian government adheres to the
"one China" policy and regards it as an important foundation of
the Sino-Fijian ties. Fiji will neither establish diplomatic ties,
nor engage itself in official contacts with Taiwan, said
Vunibobo.  
</P>
</TEXT>
