<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Issue of Human Rights Gains Momentum in Africa: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Salim Ahmed Salim,
Secretary General of the Organization of African Unity (OAU),
said today that "the issue of human and peoples' rights has
gained momentum" in Africa.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks here when opening the conference of
ministers of justice and attorneys general on the establishment
of an African court on human and peoples' rights.
</P>
<P>
The first meeting of African ministers of justice organized by
the OAU "is a clear demonstration of the fact that the issue of
human and peoples' rights has gained momentum" in the poor
continent, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Salim said the issue of human and peoples' rights "is
not a luxury, neither is it a fashion which is imported from
outside Africa", adding that "the struggle of African people for
freedom and dignity was basically a struggle for human and
peoples' rights."
</P>
<P>
He said, "Human rights need to be observed, promoted,
respected and protected so as to ensure that the energies, the
intelligence and the talents of the peoples can be released and
channeled towards productive activities in an atmosphere devoid
of physical and moral threat."
</P>
<P>
After recalling the efforts aimed at promoting human rights in
the continent, Salim said the two-day ministerial meeting
will consider a draft protocol on the establishment of an African
court on human and peoples' rights.
</P>
<P>
"The establishment of the court will clearly have far-reaching
positive implications for the respect of human and peoples'
rights in our continent," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The draft protocol will be discussed at this ministerial
meeting and submitted to the coming meeting of the OAU Council of
Ministers expected to hold at the beginning of 1998 in Luanda, a
special session devoted to the human rights situation in Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
