<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Arms Inspector Arrives In Baghdad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 12 (Xinhua) -- U.N. chief arms Inspector
Richard Butler arrived in Baghdad Friday morning on his first
visit to Iraq since the last month's crisis between Iraq and the
U.N..
</P>
<P>
Butler, chairman of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) on
dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction will hold talks
with a number of Iraqi officials on the development of relations
between Iraq and the commission, the Iraqi News Agency reported
without giving further details.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Butler's visit is aimed at convincing the
Iraqi leadership to allow the U.N. inspection teams to enter and
search presidential palaces, an issue considered by Iraq as
jeopardizing its sovereignty and violating its national security.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that Butler's talks with Iraqi officials
will be sensitive and crucial to both Iraq and the commission.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council has voiced it supports the commission
and its executive chairman in carrying out their mission of
destroying Iraq's banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. inspectors' work in Iraq has lasted about three weeks
since they were allowed to return and resume work in Baghdad late
last month.
</P>
<P>
On October 29, Baghdad threatened to expel U.S. inspectors
working with the UNSCOM on charges of spying and hindering the
lifting of the seven-year-old U.N. sanctions against Iraq, setting
off the Iraq-U.N. standoff.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions imposed after Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait can
only be lifted when the weapons inspectors verify that Iraq is
free of weapons of mass destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0109 </DOCNO>
