<HEADLINE> China Sails into Final at Asian Women's Soccer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Defending Champions China
cruised into the final of the 11th Asian Women's Soccer
Championship as they romped to a 10-0 victory over Chinese Taipei
here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Now the home side have only the DPR Koreans, whom they hammered
3-1 in the group competitions, standing between them and an
unprecedented six-straight-time Asian champions.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day's other semifinal, DPR Korea nipped Japan
1-0 to make the final and clinch one of the three Asian berths for
Women's World Cup Soccer Championship in the United States in 1999.
</P>
<P>
A far superior Chinese team wasted no time in meaning business
to their pushover opponents as they went 1-0 ahead when the game
was only two minutes old and doubled their lead three minutes
later.
</P>
<P>
They had the ball in the net four more times before the
interval and Headcoach Ma Yuanan rang the change at the second
half to rest up veteran players.
</P>
<P>
The lone moment Chinese Taipei threatened in this lopsided
match came after 65 minutes as striker Lin Chi Yi hit the left
post on a rare counter-attack.
</P>
<P>
China closed their brilliant scoring show with an incredible
zero angle goal in the 85th by 30-year-old striker Liu Ailing, who
came on target for four times in the match. 
</P>
</TEXT>
