<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN to Press Japan for Balanced Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) will press Japan for a more balanced trade
when their leaders meet in Kuala Lumpur next week, a Philippine
government official said today.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the nine ASEAN member countries will discuss
trade relations with Japan after their own informal summit to be
held in the Malaysian capital of Kuala Lumpur on December 14-16,
Philippine Foreign Undersecretary Rodolfo Severino told reporters.
</P>
<P>
After the informal summit, ASEAN leaders will hold collective
and individual meetings with the heads of state of Japan, China
and South Korea, he said.
</P>
<P>
Severino said ASEAN leaders are expected to explore with
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto measures to balance and
improve their bilateral trade with Tokyo through the reduction of
Japan's trade barriers.
</P>
<P>
Severino, however, declined to specify details on the ASEAN
approach to the issue, saying ASEAN leaders have yet to approve
and finalize the package they will present to Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
Severino will take over as ASEAN secretary-general on January
1.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
