<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: HK Shares End Week's Trading Nearly 8 percent Lower (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong shares ended the
week's volatile trading nearly 8 percent lower compared with the
previous week, dragged down by the deepened regional financial
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The key Hang Seng Index shed 912.94 points or 7.92 percent in
the five trading sessions, with heavy losses recorded in the three
sessions from Tuesday through to Thursday.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Hong Kong shares rose 195.34 points, or 1.69
percent, to end at 11,722.94, building on the previous week's gain
of 1,008.68 points or close to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the shares dropped for the first time in four
sessions as profit-taking and weakness in the region made a dent
in the local market. The Hang Seng Index fell 232.28 points, or
1.98 percent, to 11,490.66.
</P>
<P>
Things were getting worse on Wednesday as higher interbank
rates and plunging currencies in the Republic of Korea (ROK) and
Indonesia drove the market further lower. The index plunged 468.25
points or 4.07 percent to finish at the intra-day low of 11,022.41.
</P>
<P>
On the heels of the two days' losses came a much steeper drop
on Thursday, when the market recorded the largest single-day loss
since the crash on October 28.
</P>
<P>
As the ROK financial crisis deepened, interbank rates shot
higher, and fears of another attack on the Hong Kong dollar
rippled through the market, the blue-chip index dived 602.19
points, or 5.46 percent, to finish at 10,420.22.
</P>
<P>
All the regional markets were thrown into chaos that
day: Japan's Nikkei-225 Index dropped 2.6 percent, Bangkok's
shares plunged 4.9 percent, Jakarta stock prices were down by
4.77 percent, the Philippine lead index fell by 4.93 percent, and
Malaysian shares collapsed 7.41 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
