<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt-Iran Talks Hailed as Big Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said today that his talks with Iranian officials in Tehran
were "extremely fruitful" in building understanding between the
two countries which are free of diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
"The talks I held with Iranian President Mohammad Khatami and
other senior state officials were extremely fruitful," said
Moussa, who returned today from Tehran after leading his country's
delegation to the just-concluded 8th Islamic Summit.
</P>
<P>
They gave a hand in understanding the stances and policies
adopted by the two parties, he added.
</P>
<P>
Telling reporters upon his arrival, Moussa said Egypt's
participation in the summit and his contact with Iranian officials
"could help create a proper atmosphere for bilateral ties."
</P>
<P>
"Tehran summit and discussions held on the sidelines in
addition to resolutions and statements released will certainly
help in creating a new atmosphere and perhaps a new
understanding," he added.
</P>
<P>
Moussa called on the former Iranian President Hashemi
Rafsanjani and reviewed Cairo-Tehran ties on Monday, on the
sidelines of the biggest event Iran has hosted since the Iranian
Islamic Revolution of 1979.
</P>
<P>
Local press quoted him as saying that Khatami and Rafsanjani
lauded the Egyptian role in the region and expressed their respect
of the Egyptian vision.
</P>
<P>
Moussa, who is the first Egyptian foreign minister to visit
Tehran since the revolution, told reporters that he will present a
detailed report to President Hosni Mubarak on the outcome of the
summit and his contacts and meetings with a number of Islamic
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Tehran and Cairo broke off their diplomatic ties after Egypt
signed the David Camp Accord with Israel in 1979, but relations
have warmed up in recent years, particularly in the fields of
economic and scientific cooperations.
</P>
<P>
Former Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati visited
Cairo last May to invite Mubarak to attend the Islamic summit.
</P>
</TEXT>
