<HEADLINE> Roundup: HK Shares End Week's Trading Nearly 8 percent Lower (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Asian jitters swept onward to New York and London, weakening
the trading in the leading Western markets.
</P>
<P>
But, following heavy losses for three days in a row, Hong Kong
equity market reversed the downturn today to rise 194.44 points,
or 1.87 percent, to close at the day's high of 10,614.66.
</P>
<P>
Steady money market rates and bargain-hunting pushed the
recovery, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
Financial Secretary Donald Tsang's remarks that the government
will continue to defend the peg also helped the market, they said.
</P>
<P>
The market opened lower this morning due to an overnight loss
on Wall Street, with the Hang Seng Index falling 294.12 points to
10,126.10 in the first 15 minutes of trading.
</P>
<P>
At the midday break, however, the index regained all its lost
ground to end 43.95 points, or 0.42 percent, higher.
</P>
<P>
Traders said a drop in money market rates lifted
sentiment. Hong Kong's three-month interbank rate edged down to
10.5 percent today from over 11 percent Thursday.
</P>
<P>
After a regular meeting of the Hong Kong Association of Banks
this afternoon, Chairman Chris Langley told reporters that the
association decided to leave deposit interest rates unchanged, in
the belief that the relatively high interbank rates in the local
money market are "a short-term phenomenon".
</P>
<P>
However, sentiment remained cautious due to continued falls in
the ROK's won and weakness in other regional currencies.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the 10,000 point psychological support level was
holding very firm and might set the stage for a further rebound in
the index next week.
</P>
<P>
The market was oversold badly this week, said Sassoon
Securities sales manager Simon Tam, who expected a turnaround in
the coming week.
</P>
<P>
He said sentiment might continue to improve next week, with
interbank rates hopefully stabilizing at current levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
