<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Opposes U.S. Restrictions on Its Carpet Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 12 (Xinhua)-- India has said that any
effort by the United States to put restrictions on its carpet
export on social grounds will constitute violation of the World
Trade Organization(WTO)'s rules, the Press Trust of India (PTI)
quoted a senior official as saying here today.
</P>
<P>
The WTO regulations do not permit any blanket ban on imports,
the official said, adding that a resolution passed at a recent
ministerial conference in Singapore holds that social clauses will
not be linked with trade restrictions or imports coming from
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The trade dispute between India and the United States was
prompted by a new U.S. law which bans imports of hand-knitted
carpets from India, Nepal and Pakistan that are without the label
of Rugmark as required by the United States.
</P>
<P>
U.S. importers insisted on using the Rugmark label of their own
after reports said that Indian carpets had been made by using
child laborers.
</P>
<P>
India was not happy with the U.S. rejection of the Kaleen label
of its carpets, which was introduced by the Indian carpet
industry.
</P>
<P>
Social clauses are violative of WTO's guidelines, the official
said, attempts at making compulsory product labeling impose trade
barriers in the guise of social concerns.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nauru, France Resume Diplomatic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Nauru and France today
resumed diplomatic ties, which was severed two years ago by Nauru
in a protest over France's nuclear testing in the South Pacific.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced by Nauru's President Kinza Clodumar,
who said it marked a new era in relations between the two
countries, the Australian Associated Press (AAP) reported.
</P>
<P>
France said it had permanently ended nuclear testing in the
South Pacific early last year after conducting a series of tests
that led to its expulsion from the South Pacific Forum and the
imposition of diplomatic, trade and military sanctions across the
region.
</P>
<P>
Since then, France has been gradually rebuilding ties in the
region, and has won support from the island nations for its strong
stand against greenhouse gases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
