<HEADLINE> ASEAN to Meet on Transnational Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Interior ministers of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) will meet in Manila
on December 18-20 to enhance regional cooperation in fighting
transnational crimes.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Interior and Local Governments Secretary Robert
Barbers said today that the meeting will discuss ways of fighting
transnational crimes, particularly terrorism, firearms smuggling,
drug trafficking and money laundering.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will be highlighted by the adoption of an "ASEAN
Declaration against Transnational Crimes" which is expected to
focus on cooperation among ASEAN members in combating crime
syndicates.
</P>
<P>
"Transnational crimes respect no borders and the ASEAN
countries recognize the need for bilateral cooperation to combat
these illicit activities," Barbers said.
</P>
<P>
Barbers said there is also the growing need for a clear and
effective regional modality to combat these forms of crimes,
especially on information change and policy coordination.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN currently groups the Philippines, Brunei, Indonesia,
Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
</TEXT>
