<HEADLINE> Chinese President Expects Good Results From Sino-American Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 12 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin said
here today that his recent visit to the United States has yielded
important results and the world welcomes the improvement of the
Sino-American relations.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the remarks while meeting with Admiral Joseph
Prueher, Commander-in-Chief of the US Pacific Command.
</P>
<P>
This proves once again that a healthy and stable Sino-American
relationship is not only in the interest of the Chinese and
Americans, but is also the wish of the people around the world, he
said.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton's visit to China is planned for next year, he
said, adding that he believes the exchange of visits by the heads
of state of China and the United States will push Sino-American
relations to a new level.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that relations between the Chinese and American armed
forces are an important part of Sino-American relations, and have
developed positively over the past year. He praised
Adm. Prueher for his efforts at promoting the development of
relations between the two armed forces.
</P>
<P>
"We take a positive attitude toward the development of
Sino-American military relations and hope these relations will
grow in a more practical and steady manner," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Prueher told Jiang that during his visit he had useful
discussions with Chinese military leaders on strengthening
relations between the two armed forces.
</P>
<P>
He said that Jiang's visit to the United States had been
successful and that the bilateral relations established by Jiang
and Clinton ensure the continued development of US-China relations.
</P>
<P>
Prueher reiterated Jiang's words that China and the
United States need to increase mutual understanding before they
build mutual trust. The two countries are now working for this
goal, Prueher added.
</P>
<P>
Present at the meeting were Gen. Fu Quanyou, chief of general
staff of the PLA, Lieut. Gen. Kui Fulin, deputy chief of PLA
general staff, You Xigui, deputy director of the general office of
the Chinese Communist Party Central Committee, and James Sasser,
US ambassador to China. 
</P>
