<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing to Open More Sectors to Outside World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Beijing will further open its
service, cultural and educational service sectors to overseas
investment, according to Beijing Mayor Jia Qinglin.
</P>
<P>
In an address to today's opening session of the Eighth
Municipal Congress of the Chinese Communist Party (CPC), Jia, who
also serves as secretary of the CPC Beijing Municipal Committee,
said Beijing must open more sectors to the outside world and
enhance its competitiveness in order to become a modernized
international metropolis.
</P>
<P>
Jia said that Beijing needs a comprehensive plan to attract
foreign investment for a number of key projects at the turn of the
century.
</P>
<P>
He noted that transnational corporations with high-level
management are expected to invest in Beijing, the Chinese capital,
and added that they are welcomed to establish regional
headquarters or subsidiary corporations.
</P>
<P>
Jia noted that Beijing would open more channels and adopt
additional means to issue securities and bonds overseas in order
to attract more foreign funds and loans.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has actually used overseas funds of some 9.41 billion
U.S. dollars over the past five years, with 138 of the world's 500
largest transnational corporations operating in the city,
according to Jia.
</P>
<P>
Jia called for the city to further perfect laws and policies
related to foreign investment and taxation, while improving its
work efficiency and investment environment.
</P>
<P>
Jia's report also listed a number of key sectors open to
foreign investment, including the new high technology, service,
modern agriculture, pillar industries, private housing and
infrastructure construction. In the report, he also paid great
attention to the development of economic and technological
development zones.
</P>
<P>
Beijing had approved 13,327 foreign-funded enterprises by the
end of November this year, with total contracted investments
standing at 21.1 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has also established 300-odd enterprises in more than
20 foreign countries and regions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Giving an Interview to Japanese Media (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 12 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin, in a
meeting today with Takuhiko Tsuruta, president of Nihon Keizai
Shimbun, and his party, urged the Japanese to draw a lesson from
history for the sustained and healthy development of Sino-Japanese
relations.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said China and Japan are separated only by a narrow strip
of water and have had friendly exchanges for more than 2,000 years
that have helped promote their economic and cultural development
and have contributed to the progress of mankind.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, the war of aggression waged by Japanese
militarists in modern times resulted in a disaster for the Chinese
and suffering for the Japanese, he said, but past experiences, if
not forgotten, can be a guide for the future.
</P>
<P>
For the past 25 years, since the normalization of Sino-Japanese
relations, Jiang said, China has witnessed the continuous growth
of bilateral relations and increasing exchanges and co-operation,
thanks to the two sides' efforts under the principles of the
Sino-Japanese Joint Statement and the Sino-Japanese Treaty for
Peace and Friendship.
</P>
<P>
"We have long set forth the expression "Sino-Japanese
friendship from generation to generation," he said, and for the
fundamental interest of the two peoples and and for the noble
cause of advancing global peace and development, the two sides
should make a concerted effort to develop good neighborly
relations oriented to the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Good political relations between the two sides are conducive to
the smooth development of economic ties and trade, and they should
try to establish constructive, long-term and stable economic
co-operation, while making long-term plans for shifting from
quantity to quality in economic and trade co-operation. The two
governments should give policy guidance to economic ties and
two-way trade by exploring new channels and co-operating in other
areas.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said he believes that the main trend in Sino-Japanese
economic co-operation is good and the potential great, and that as
long as the two countries proceed in a mood of friendship, handle
matters properly, and make full use of their respective
advantages, bilateral economic ties and trade will see new
progress.
</P>
<P>
Jiang discussed China's basic policies for Southeast Asia, and
said that the development of long-term good neighborly relations
with Southeast Asia is an important component part of China's
foreign policy. China wants to join ASEAN countries in
establishing neighborly trust and co-operative relations oriented
toward the 21st century, with a view toward maintaining regional
peace, stability, and development, and promoting regional economic
and technological co-operation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Both sides should gradually resolve their individual
differences through equal and friendly consultation, and they
should seek a common ground while allowing some differences that
cannot be resolved for the time being to remain so that they do
not have a negative effect on the overall development of
good-neighborly relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Giving an Interview to Japanese Media (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
About China's entry into the World Trade Organization (WTO),
Jiang said that China has met the essential requirements for
membership and that without China's participation, the WTO's trade
system is incomplete. China is a developing nation, he said, and
only when this is recognized can there be a balance between rights
and obligations.
</P>
<P>
He said that there has been some progress in negotiations and
bilateral talks and that China and some trade partners have
reached agreements. He added that he hopes all parties involved
can be far-sighted and make China one of the WTO members at an
early date because it would be beneficial to all.
</P>
<P>
No matter what the outcome of the negotiations, he went on to
say, the reforms and opening-up and modernization drive will
continue, as will China's economic development.
</P>
<P>
He also described China's policies for state-owned enterprises
and the economic development of central and western parts of the
country, and said that the reform of state-owned firms is the
focus of economic restructuring. "We are striving to revitalize
them by setting up a modern enterprise system, combining reforms,
restructuring, and reshuffling with a tightening up of management,
a strategic restructuring, encouraging mergers, regulating
bankruptcies, increasing efficiency by reducing employment, and
beginning a re-employment project for laid-off workers."
</P>
<P>
"Our goals are to bring most large and medium-sized
money-losing state-owned enterprises out of difficulties by the
end of this century and to create a new situation for reforming
and developing these firms," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since the reforms and opening-up began, Jiang said, coastal
parts of eastern China have had swift development but that
development in the western part of the country is also
increasing. However, it still lags far behind, he said, noting
that the country is doing everything possible to solve this
problem.
</P>
<P>
The relevant measures include: giving more state assistance to
the central and western parts of China, giving priority to their
infrastructure and exploration of resources, gradually using a
regulated finance-transfer payment system, encouraging more
domestic and overseas investment in these areas, further
developing various forms of co-operation between central and
western and rather more-developed eastern coastal parts of China,
Jiang explained.
</P>
<P>
In this way, the gap between the central, western and eastern
parts of China can be narrowed, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- British Prime Minister Tony Blair broke a 76-year taboo by
receiving the leader of Sinn Fein Jerry Adams in his office in
number 10 Downing Street on Thursday. This was the first time for
a British prime minister to meet a Sinn Fein leader in London
since 1921, when Lloyd George and Michael Collins ratified the
partition of Ireland following a bloody conflict in the country.
</P>
<P>
-- International terrorist Illitch Ramirez Sanchez, known as
"Carlos," will appear Friday at the Assize Court in Paris over
charge of three murders committed in rue Toullier, Paris, on June
27, 1975, in which two inspectors of the Direction of Territorial
Security and a Lebanese man were killed.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- While the crisis in stock markets amplified in Asia, the
Wall Street and European stock markets once again are worried
about its impact on economic growth. For the fourth consecutive
day Thursday, the won of South Korea dropped by 10 percent,
despite an agreement with the International Monetary Fund and
international aid. The European stock exchange markets also
fell: Paris by 3.54 percent, London 1.84 percent, Frankfurt 2.12
percent, while Hong Kong stock index fell by 5.46 percent, Seoul
5.6 percent, Tokyo by 2.6 percent and New York Dow Jones index
1.63 percent.
</P>
<P>
-- The chiefs of state and government of the 15 European Union
(EU) countries will meet Friday in Luxembourg to decide which
countries can be absorbed by EU in the first wave of its
enlargement. While expressing ardent support to EU enlargement,
France also wishes the EU to take into account the financial and
institutional aspects in the "global process" of enlargement. But
Germany wants the summit to only focus on the issue of
enlargement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
