<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Develops Diagnostic Kit for HIV Patients </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 12 (Xinhua)-- India's biochemists at the
Delhi University have developed a simple two-minute test for
simultaneous detection of human immuno-deficiency virus (HIV) that
causes AIDS, official sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The test requires just a drop of blood, a glass slide and a
special cocktail reagent which they have developed. The result can
be seen with naked eyes and no instruments are needed. If the
addition of the reagent caused clumping of the blood, the sample
is positive for HIV, otherwise it is negative.
</P>
<P>
A cocktail of relevant fusion protein are used in the reagent
to detect HIV strains. The reagent has been evaluated in
commercially available blood samples and also in a large number of
samples taken from Indian patients.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Foreign Exchange Reserves Hit New Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Latest estimates show that
Bangladesh's foreign exchange reserves have fallen to 1.5 billion
U.S. dollars, Bangladesh's national weekend newspaper Holiday
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The country's foreign exchange reserves were falling
drastically, raising doubts over the government's ability to face
any sudden external shock, the newspaper warned.
</P>
<P>
"This is an alarming sign," the newspaper quoted one senior
banker as saying.
</P>
<P>
The amount of foreign exchange reserves is equivalent to only
two months' import bill, the newspaper said, adding that ideally,
the country needs reserves enough for meeting at least four
months' import payments.
</P>
<P>
This drastic fall in the foreign exchange reserves was
attributable to the recent payment of a substantial amount to the
Asian Clearing Union, Bangladesh Bank (the central bank) officials
said.
</P>
<P>
Even reserves at the level of 1.6 billion dollars, as
Bangladeshi Finance Minister Shah AMS Kibria had said last week,
were not "comfortable" for an economy like Bangladesh, said an
economist working for the Bangladesh Institute of Development
Studies.
</P>
<P>
Another senior banker working at a national commercial bank
said the central bank officials had been asked to chalk out some
immediate steps in this regard, the newspaper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
