<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Wool Prices Fall Before Stabilizing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Wool prices dipped this week
before stabilizing at the last sales for the year, the Australian
Council of Wool Exporters said today.
</P>
<P>
The eastern market indicator dropped 10 Australian cents (6.6
U.S. cents) to close at 698 cents (462 U.S. cents) a kilogram
clean while the western indicator slid 9 Australian cents (6 U.S.
cents) from the last Fremantle sale a fortnight ago to finish at
644 Australian cents (427 U.S. cents).
</P>
<P>
About 132,030 bales were offered, with a pass-in rate of 19
percent.
</P>
<P>
"The market fell initially early in the week but stabilized on
the final day with the easing of the Australian dollar against the
U.S. dollar," the council said in its weekly wool market review.
</P>
<P>
"Generally prices were lower in the fine and medium wools due
to uncertain demand from European buyers, and the Asian economic
crisis continues to have an effect on the market."
</P>
<P>
China's snapping up of coarser wool kept prices for these
micron categories firm.
</P>
<P>
Sales will resume on January 5 in Melbourne and Fremantle with
about 74,900 bales rostered for sale.
</P>
<P>
In its weekly wool report, Wesfarmers Dalgety said the
stabilization suggested that prices should hold about this level
when the market re-opens.
</P>
<P>
Other factors expected to support prices include the continued
weakness of the Australian dollar, Chinese demand for medium to
broad wools and smaller quantities for sale in January.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore when the market resumes in January, prices are
expected to open at similar levels to this week," the report said.
</P>
<P>
"However the outlook beyond this is dependent on the extent of
the impact of the Asian economic crisis," it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
