<HEADLINE> Chile's Ruling Coalition Claims Election Victory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Chile's ruling coalition
claimed victory in Thursday's legislative elections, said
preliminary results released by the Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
With 98 percent of the ballots counted, the Concertacion, the
ruling coalition, won 50.54 percent of the valid votes.
</P>
<P>
The Concertacion includes the Christian Democratic Party, the
Party for Democracy and the Socialist Party.
</P>
<P>
"The government and the Concertacion have once again won the
people's backing," President Eduardo Frei, a Christian Democrat,
said.
</P>
<P>
The opposition coalition of the Independent Democratic Union
and the National Renovation Party took away 36.25 percent of the
votes.
</P>
<P>
The elections were to renew the 120 seats of the lower house
and 20 of the 38 elected seats in the Senate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
