<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Project Brings Greater Hope To Chinese Children And Their Parents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 12 (Xinhua) -- School-age children are not
the only beneficiaries of Project Hope, China's largest charitable
organization for education, as their families became better-off as
well.
</P>
<P>
Twelve-year-old Hu Xiaolin resumed her studies at the Jinzhai
Hope Primary School in east China's Anhui Province. The school,
which was built in May, 1990 with Project Hope funds, was the
first in China.
</P>
<P>
Then, Hu started to teach her parents some planting techniques
she learned at school three years ago, and they started planting
Chinese cabbage, cucumbers, and green peppers in
plastic-film-covered sheds. The money earned from the vegetables
helped increase their income, and they moved out of their old
thatched cottage and into a two-story brick house this spring.
</P>
<P>
The project not only helps poor school-age children go to
school, but turns primary schools into sources of information
about agronomy and technology, according to Xu Yongguang,
secretary general of the China Youth Development Foundation
(CYDF), which began Project Hope eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
CYDF got Hope primary schools to add vocational education to
their basic curriculum when it found out that most rural students
return to their village to farm instead of going on to college,
after they receive a nine-year education. This is particularly
true in poor areas.
</P>
<P>
In the case of Jinzhai, students from 47 Hope primary schools
in the county have added two books to their school bags: one
applies to local conditions and local needs, the other is about
planting techniques.
</P>
<P>
The two special textbooks, which were compiled by local
education department, discuss silkworm breeding, white mulberry
planting, raising gastrodia elata, a type of traditional Chinese
medicine, cultivating the Chinese chestnut, and processing tea.
</P>
<P>
And, at the Quxian Hope Primary School in nearby Zhejiang
Province, students even get to practice what they learn, on the
school's farm by planting trees and flowers, raising pigs, and
processing feed.
</P>
<P>
CYDF offers training courses in agronomy and technology at its
teachers' training center. It also plans to allocate special funds
for a group of Hope primary schools for vocational education.
</P>
<P>
In the past eight years, Project Hope has helped 1.5 million
dropouts return to school and has built more than 6,000 primary
schools, with nearly one billion yuan (approximately 120 million
US dollars) in donations from China and overseas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
