<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: French Wine Dealer in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Alain Ponzard came to Hong
Kong six months before the handover to look after the regional
office of SOPEXA, a French semi-governmental agency to promote the
country's wines and food around the world.
</P>
<P>
Now more than five months after the handover, Ponzard said that
the biggest change that drew his attention after July 1 was on
the mailbox -- the British royal crown was replaced by a humming
bird logo of the Special Administrative Region's Postal Department.
</P>
<P>
Business, as usual, means more and more work to do, said the
Frenchman. On the heel of a Medoc wine tasting seminar last month
for professionals, the managing director of SOPEXA's Hong Kong
Office is now busy with a six-week French Wine Festival which
targets men in the street.
</P>
<P>
His cozy office is filled with bundles of pamphlets featuring
three high-heeled glasses of wines on the cover -- for publicity
use at the on-going festival.
</P>
<P>
The small brochure introduces to beginners the basic knowledge
of wines from France, ranging from the classification to
characteristics of French wines, from wine-brewing regions in
France to how to see, smell, taste, and store wines.
</P>
<P>
Wine, more than anything else, is immediately associated with
France, said the little book's opening sentence. That's the
competitive edge for Ponzard to promote French wine in Hong Kong
and other parts of Asia.
</P>
<P>
He said that more and more people in Hong Kong and in Asia have
found favorites with wines as they come to believe that drinking
wines is healthy and fashionable.
</P>
<P>
Fast economic growth in Asia has also made it possible for the
increasingly affluent population to afford a variety of wines,
either cheap Vins de Table for a dozen HK dollars (1.5 U.S.
dollars) or an expensive bottle of Appellations d'Origine
Controlee (AOC) for more than 10,000 HK dollars (1,280 U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Ponzard couldn't help getting excited when talking about French
wine, which is on the top of his marketing list in Asia. "Unlike
the saturated European market, Asia is booming with great
potential," said the Frenchman. "The market is growing so fast
that there are a lot of opportunities to seize and a lot of things
to do."
</P>
<P>
The French wine is dominating in the Hong Kong market, where
two out of three bottles of still wine were imported from France
in the first six months of this year. Though a considerable amount
of the imported wine is for re-export to other places of Asia, the
local consumption has surged into the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The amount of wine consumed by Hong Kong people, measured by
duty-paid imports of wine, surged by 22 percent from the previous
year to reach 5.88 million liters in 1996. The momentum continued
into the first half of this year, when local consumption rose
sharply by 90 percent over the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Despite the remarkable increase, Ponzard said that less than
one liter of wine is consumed per head per year in Hong Kong, far
below the world average consumption of eight liters per person
per year.
</P>
<P>
"The discrepancy indicates vast potential for growth," he said.
"But we must work hard to keep the leading position because of the
keen competition." Other wine-brewing countries the United States
and Australia, Italy, Chile and Spain, all made a foray into Hong
Kong, which plays a pivotal role in the Asian market.
</P>
<P>
Ponzard said the biggest difficulty now he has encountered is
that he cannot understand Cantonese, the Chinese dialect used by
over 90 percent of Hong Kong's 6.3 million people.
</P>
<P>
"I'm now learning Cantonese," he said. "And I hope I could
communicate smoothly with my clients someday to know what they
like or don't like."
</P>
<P>
His two daughters, one two and the other five, are also
learning Cantonese. Ponzard moved his four-member family from
Paris to Hong Kong as he took the current post.
</P>
<P>
The Frenchman fell in love with the Chinese culture nine years
ago when he traveled to China for the first time. "That's why I
was happy when a job in Hong Kong is available to me," he said.
The Chinese language is imaginative in this Frenchman's mind. For
instance, he said, in Chinese movie is called "electric shadow".
</P>
<P>
"I want my daughters to go to school in Hong Kong," said
Ponzard, who believed that the experience in Asia could help
broaden their vision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
