<HEADLINE> Ugandan Herbalists Advised to Adhere to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan herbalists and
healers are advised to adhere their professional ethics, The
Monitor reported today.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Batte Salongo, the publicity secretary of the National
Council of Traditional Healers and Herbalists Association
(NACOTHA), urged the herbalists and traditional healers to stop
diagnosing diseases by spirit.
</P>
<P>
The spirit-guided herbs have caused many deaths, he told
NACOTHA practitioners in central Mubende district.
</P>
<P>
NACOTHA will revoke its certificate to those practitioners who
failed to fulfill its by-laws, Batte warned.
</P>
<P>
Traditional medicine enjoys high popularity among local
residents, especially among women and in rural areas. But
spirit-guided herbs are tarnishing its merit, Batte noted.
</P>
<P>
Some herbalists impose high fee from patients, local residents
here said. Batte advised herbalists to launch income-generating
industries such as goat and poultry raising for his families,
avoiding exorbitant fees for patients. 
</P>
</TEXT>
