<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Real Estate Prices Drop Sharply in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Israel's housing prices
declined by five to 15 percent during the last 12 months, local
newspaper The Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Israeli industry sources as saying that the
sharpest decline was felt in luxury homes selling for 2 million to
2.5 million U.S. dollars along the coastal plain, which lost 15
percent of their value. In some cases their market value fell by
30 percent.
</P>
<P>
While prices of larger homes fell sharply, the prices of
two-bedroom apartments remained almost unchanged. The market for
these flats is relatively stable as the demand for small
apartments remains high.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources said that the decline in housing prices is
mainly attributed to the steady decline in immigration and to the
general slowing-down of the economy.
</P>
<P>
The influx of new immigrants in the early 1990s is widely seen
as the main engine behind the overall sharp rise in housing prices
in this decade.
</P>
<P>
Another factor impacting the market is the decline in the
number of housing starts, which dropped 18 percent in the first
nine months of the year. If this decline continues, a shortage may
be felt in the market within a year, experts believe.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources said that many contractors are postponing
new projects and some have even returned land to the Israel
Lands Administration.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that while it is hard to predict when
the market will recover, the general estimate is that if the
overall economy starts accelerating in the second half of
1998, it will generate increased demand for homes, which in
turn will result in higher property prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Leader Hails Sino-New Zealand Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 12 (Xinhua)-- There exist broad prospects
for the development of economic cooperation and trade between
China and New Zealand on the basis of equality and mutual benefit
as the two economies are complementary with each other, a Chinese
leader said here today.
</P>
<P>
Li Ruihuan, chairman of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) National Committee, said at a
meeting with Michael Hardie Boys, governor-general of New Zealand,
that although the two countries are different in social system and
ideology, there is no conflict of fundamental interests between
them.
</P>
<P>
Boys said that in the past 25 years, New Zealand have paid more
 attention to China, a great country with a long history. The New
Zealand people admire the significant achievements the Chinese
people have made and would like to learn a lot from the country.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his hope that through people-to-people contacts
and cooperation in international organizations, the relations
between the two countries would be further advanced.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of China's domestic situation, Li said recent years
have witnessed great progress in various sectors of China, which
the Chinese people are pleased to see and satisfied with and the
international community has valued highly.
</P>
<P>
Historical experiences have proved however that it is
imperative to be sober-minded when tremendous fruits are yielded
and development is smooth, Li said, adding that a big gap still
remains between China and developed countries as far as the level
of economic development and science and technology is concerned.
</P>
<P>
"So, we must have a thorough understanding of the
contradictions and difficulties and tell our people the truth,"
Li said. "Only in this way can people get a full picture of the
situation and be prepared for overcoming various difficulties."
</P>
<P>
China has a long way to go to catch up with developed
countries, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Li, who arrived here yesterday, is on a four-day official
goodwill visit to New Zealand at the invitation of the New
Zealand government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
