<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are business
briefs from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The U.S. company United Parcel Service (UPS), the
world's largest courier firm with 22 billion U.S. dollars in
annual revenues, has set up office in Lebanon, local newspaper the
Daily Star reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
With the launch of the Lebanon operations, UPS' Lebanese
customers will be able to have their packages and documents
delivered to over 200 countries and territories worldwide through
the company's services, said Roger Saade, general manager for UPS
Lebanon, at a press conference in Beirut on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The operations were officially launched on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Damian Bond, Middle East managing director for UPS, said the
lifting of U.S. restrictions against U.S. business activities in
Lebanon last July has made it possible for UPS to open direct
operations here.
</P>
<P>
Due to the restrictions, he said, UPS is the last of the big
express shipping companies to come to Beirut, but the company has
been involved in inbound business here through its partner firm
United Courier for several years, with annual growth rates of 35
percent.
</P>
<P>
He added that shipments out of Beirut will be routed through
Dubai, the United Arab Emirates, or London, and for the time being
the firm will use commercial carriers like the Middle East or
Emirates airlines for its Beirut traffic.
</P>
<P>
DHL and Amman-based Aramex currently dominate the Lebanese
market with the presence of the US-based Federal Express.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanese industrial exports reached around 26 million
U.S. dollars during November, compared with approximately 24
million dollars in October, local newspapers reported.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that Saudi Arabia led the list of countries
importing Lebanese industrial goods, followed by Syria, France,
Jordan, Egypt, Russia and Britain.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- The International Fund for Agricultural Development
has decided to earmark 70 million U.S. dollars to finance three
agricultural development projects in Syria, local media reported.
</P>
<P>
These projects are located in the southern, northern and
coastal areas with the aim of promoting the living conditions of
rural youths and women, reclamation of land, and offering of
agricultural loans.
</P>
<P>
The fund is also examining an important Syrian project, the
cost of which exceeds 100 million U.S. dollars for the development
of desert and pasture lands in eight Syrian governorates. It will
be jointly financed by the fund, the Arab social development fund
as well as the Syrian government.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's housing prices declined by five to 15
percent during the last 12 months, local newspaper The Jerusalem
Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Israeli industry sources as saying that the
sharpest decline was felt in luxury homes selling for 2 million to
2.5 million U.S. dollars along the coastal plain, which lost 15
percent of their value. In some cases their market value fell by
30 percent.
</P>
<P>
While prices of larger homes fell sharply, the prices of
two-bedroom apartments remained almost unchanged. The market for
these flats is relatively stable as the demand for small
apartments remains high.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources said that the decline in housing prices is
mainly attributed to the steady decline in immigration and to the
general slowing-down of the economy.
</P>
<P>
The influx of new immigrants in the early 1990s is widely seen
as the main engine behind the overall sharp rise in housing prices
in this decade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
