<HEADLINE> Stocks Continue Falling in Tokyo on Worries Over Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Tokyo stock prices continued
falling Friday with the key Nikkei index ending below the 16,000
mark for the first time in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei average of 225 selected issues on the First Section
of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 145.85 points or 0.91 percent
from Thursday's close to 15,904.30 as traders were weighed down by
lingering pessimism over the sagging economy.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
issues on the First Section, sank 16.90 points or 1.39 percent to
1,198.84.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the First Section came to an estimated 970 million
shares, up from Thursday's 422.09 million shares with Hokkaido
Takushoku Bank as the leader.
</P>
<P>
On the third consecutive day decline, the Nikkei index closed
below the 16,000 line for the first time since November 25,
underlining the weakness of the market fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
Traders said that Thursday's basic agreement in the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party to support the financial system with 10
trillion yen (about 76.9 billion U.S. dollars) in public funds was
insufficient to spark buying.
</P>
<P>
The 10-year low of the Korean stock market hit steelmakers and
chemical firms hard, causing the Nikkei to momentarily lose more
than 300 points, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,329 issues listed on the First Section, losers outpaced
gainers by 778 to 361, with 142 issues unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
