<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sweden-U.N.-China Plan Joint Effort to Protect Ozone Layer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) will launch a project in China that will promote
the use of new technologies to help reduce the use of
ozone-depleting substances (ODS) in the country's solvent sector,
a U.N. official said.
</P>
<P>
The Swedish government recently donated one million U.S. dollars
to UNDP for this project.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.N. official, the project will demonstrate
ODS-free cleaning technologies, and establish a sustainable
technology transfer mechanism that would allow China to
disseminate and apply these technologies in the use of cleaning
solvents.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the project, about 200 people including trainers,
government officials and managers of enterprises will have been
trained for the adoption of new technologies. Also, at least three
demonstration sites for cost-effective and appropriate ozone-free
and process/resource efficient technologies will have been set up
in Shanghai, the official said.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 10,000 tons of ozone-depleting substances are used
annually in solvents used in China. The UNDP hopes that the
project will have a positive impact on both the global and
national environment.
</P>
<P>
Sweden will provide the funds to UNDP through the Swedish
International Development Cooperation Agency to support the
implementation and monitoring of the project. The project will be
carried out by China's National Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
