<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gifts to Chinese Leaders on Display </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 12 (Xinhua) -- More than 400 gifts received
by top Chinese officials since the founding of new China in 1949
are on display at the Chinese Revolutionary Museum adjacent the
Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
The collection is one-fourth of the gifts from governments,
senior leaders, non-governmental organizations and individuals in
more than 150 countries. They include gold and silverware, jade
and stone carvings, chinaware, paintings and handicrafts.
</P>
<P>
A swan pair with three children, chinaware sent from former
U.S. President Richard Nixon to Mao Zedong in February of 1972, is
among the numerous gifts on display.
</P>
<P>
Gifts received by Deng Xiaoping include a wooden bird from the
U.S. government in 1979 and a silver sailboat by then Japanese
Prime Minister Nakasone Yasuhiro in 1984.
</P>
<P>
Gifts for President Jiang Zemin and other third-generation
leaders are also on display.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition is sponsored by the International Friendship
Museum of China, which specializes in collecting, storing,
studying and showing foreign gifts for Chinese leaders. The museum
was founded in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
