<HEADLINE> Uganda to Inject $500m in Telecom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has planned to inject
over 500 billion shillings (some 500 million U.S. Dollars) into
telecommunications industries, The New Vision quoted a minister
as saying today.
</P>
<P>
The sum will be spent in the next five years, said John
Nasasira, the Minister of Works, Transport and Communications.
</P>
<P>
The reward for the investment will be the improvement of
teledensity from 400 people now to 50 a line, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing on the second National Program for Information
Analysts (Napia) workshop earlier this week, the minister said
the main problem faced with by the country now is lack of enough
qualified specialists.
</P>
<P>
The high technology industries are the thrust of the
sustainable development his government is searching for, the
minister added. The thrust is most likely information, he
estimated.
</P>
<P>
But the service of qualified information specialists is
unaffordable due to the high training fees causing high salaries,
the minister noted.
</P>
<P>
The workshop is characterized by a warm response from people
involved in telecommunications industry in the country, said
Norah Mulira, the sponsorer of the workshop and the acting
director of the Institute of Computer Science in Makerere
University. Many participants of the workshop are managers,
system developers, system designers, programmers and other
professionals. The attendants of the last year's workshop were
only trainers.
</P>
<P>
Developing information industry is an opportunity for a
developing country to catch up with the developed ones, Mulira
told the workshop. 
</P>
</TEXT>
