<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cholera Toll Increases to 29 in Nairobi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The cholera toll in Nairobi
over the past 10 days rose to 29 with 15 more deaths reported
between last Saturday and yesterday, according to a Daily Nation
report today.
</P>
<P>
Jonah Kitheka, Executive Director of the Provide International
Center, said that the center was taking care of 20 cholera
patients in two tents pitched in the compound while scores lay
unattended in their homes.
</P>
<P>
He noted that "the situation is deteriorating day after day,
and with the water shortage, the disease is spreading rapidly."
</P>
<P>
The daily newspaper said that the cholera outbreak came at a
time of an acute water shortage in the capital city and its
environs with almost all residential estates being affected by
water shortage.
</P>
<P>
Patrick Kirui, Nairobi medical officer of health said that
with the onset of the current rain season, the city council had
foreseen an outbreak of cholera and had set up a special
committee to formulate control measures.
</P>
<P>
The committee had gone round the city and isolated a few cases
which council hospitals were handled until the nurses' strike
started 14 days ago.
</P>
<P>
Kitheka noted that they were finding it hard to cope with the
swelling number of victims since desperate cases could not be
referring to the Kenyatta National Hospital owing to the on-going
nurses' strike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
