<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End 1 Percent Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Plummeting resource stocks
forced the Australian share market down by almost 1 percent today
while weaker world markets continued to weigh on investor
sentiment.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries Index ended 22.8 points weaker at 2494 while
the All Resources lost 30.6 points or 2.8 percent to 1056.1,
reversing gains made in the week.
</P>
<P>
"Commodity prices around the world are still looking very weak
and people are selling (resources stocks) continually -- they just
can't find any level of support at this stage," Reynolds &AMP; Co's
Peter Struk said.
</P>
<P>
"New York was down, London was down, as were Tokyo, commodities
and gold so we never had a chance."
</P>
<P>
Brokers said investor sentiment was weak in the wake of the
collapse of the Korean won in foreign exchange markets.
</P>
<P>
The industrials sector held up reasonably well, shedding 15.7
points to reach 4294.8.
</P>
<P>
Resources heavyweights led the declines in resources, with BHP
dropping 53 cents or 3.9 percent, Woodside 40 cents, WMC 23 cents
and MIM a further 4 cents.
</P>
<P>
The gold index improved 4.1 points to 858.3 while in Sydney
bullion was trading 1.35 dollars lower at 283.45 U.S. dollars per
ounce.
</P>
<P>
Australia's big four banks all lost ground, with NAB slipping 6
cents, ANZ 25 cents, CBA 15 cents and Westpac 9 cents.
</P>
<P>
National turnover reached 323.78 million, valued at 768.35
million Australian dollars (507.11 million U.S. dollars). Falls
outnumbered rises 627 to 431 while 382 remained steady.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
