<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Kicks Off Anti-Dumping Investigation (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Foreign Trade
and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC) Wednesday announced an
investigation into the dumping of foreign newsprint on the Chinese
market.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has made it clear by this action that it
will not allow overseas companies to dump commodities in China and
will resort to legal means to oppose the practice.
</P>
<P>
Information from the State Commission of Economy and Trade
indicates that some imported foreign commodities have seriously
damaged such Chinese industrial sectors as steel, oil, sugar,
machine tools, program-controlled switchboards, plywood, glass,
wool, color film and newsprint.
</P>
<P>
Some foreign commodities were dumped at low prices to occupy
the Chinese market, an official said, causing serious damages to
some of China's industries.
</P>
<P>
China's newsprint industry has suffered the most from the
dumping of foreign commodities. Foreign newsprint is sold for 350
U.S. dollars per ton in China this year, but the international
market price for newsprint is 550 U.S. dollars per ton.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that if the situation continues, China's newsprint
producers will completely collapse and be replaced by foreign
commodities.
</P>
<P>
On Nov. 10, several newsprint enterprises from Jilin,
Guangdong, Sichuan and Jiangxi provinces formally asked MOFTEC to
investigate dumping by firms in the United States, Canada and
the Republic of Korea (ROK).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Kicks Off Anti-Dumping Investigation (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A MOFTEC spokesman said that anti-dumping is a legal way to
combat unequal competition and to protect domestic industries. The
anti-dumping agreement of the World Trade Organization (WTO) also
encourages legal remedies.
</P>
<P>
In 1979, the European Union carried out anti-dumping
investigations into China's exports of soluble saccharin.
</P>
<P>
Foreign countries have raised 280 anti-dumping cases over
China-made commodities for export, involving tens of billions
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Some overseas companies in recent years, with the intention of
capturing the Chinese market, have dumped their products at very
low prices causing losses of tens of billions RMB yuan. Such
dumping has forced Chinese enterprises to lay off workers, caused
major setbacks for new emerging industries and driven many factories
to the edge of bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
MOFTEC will begin dealing with anti-dumping applications from
domestic enterprises this year. Investigations will be conducted
of imported commodities that have entered the Chinese market at
lower-than-normal prices which resulted in real damages to
domestic industries.
</P>
<P>
As China's opening-up drive expands, China's domestic market
will be opened wider to the outside world, said the MOFTEC
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"It has become more and more important that industrial
companies in China should study hard, master, and eventually learn
to use the anti-dumping weapon to avoid damages caused by the
dumping of foreign commodities on the Chinese market," said the
MOFTEC spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He urged Chinese companies to resist unfair competition from
foreign commodities, and to protect the legitimate rights of
domestic industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Pilots in Training in Turkey: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Israeli pilots of fighter
jets have carried out 120 sorties in Turkey this year, many of
them practice for long-range missions, a newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The English daily The Jerusalem Post quoted a senior defense
official as saying that Israeli CH-53 transport helicopters have
also recorded over 120 sorties in the past year, since Israeli
airspace is limited.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that Israeli helicopter pilots have become
familiar with the Turkish terrain. This helped them respond
quickly to a Turkish request last July to put out a fire at the
country's main munitions plant.
</P>
<P>
Israel and Turkey singed a defense cooperation agreement in
early 1996, which allows pilots from both countries to train in
each other's countries. Israeli pilots have very restricted
airspace for training because of the small size of their own
country.
</P>
<P>
For its part, Turkish pilots are about to enhance their flight
training with advanced Israeli simulators and technology.
</P>
<P>
Israel's long-range flight training is mainly aimed at
launching cross-border air attacks against targets of enemy
countries that pose threats to Israeli security.
</P>
<P>
The military cooperation has come under increasing criticism
by Muslim countries. On Wednesday, Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel withdrew from the eighth Islamic summit held in Iran's
capital Teheran to avoid facing additional criticism of Turkey's
ties with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Demirel defended Turkey's military accord with Israel, saying
the agreement is bilateral and does not pose a threat to any
third country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a joint military maneuver among Israel, Turkey and
the United States is to be held January 5. Turkey said the aim of
the exercises is to develop joint training for sea-air search and
rescue operations among the three nations' fleets.
</P>
<P>
In another move to boost the bilateral military cooperation,
the semi-annual strategic talks between Turkey and Israel are to
be held in Turkish capital Ankara on December 22.
</P>
<P>
The talks, the third since the 1996 military alliance was
formed, are aimed at furthering an evaluation of joint threats,
such as ballistic missile threats from Iran and Syria, and
responses to them as well as numerous defense industry issues, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, exchange of visits by military leaders has also
intensified between Turkey and Israel. Earlier this month, Israeli
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai visited Ankara to discuss
boosting military ties, as well as Israel's supply of weapons to
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
On December 21, Turkish Defense Ministry Undersecretary Tuncer
Kilinc is to visit Israel to discuss details of the agreement of
modernizing Turkey's F-4 fighters by Israel. And Turkish Land
Forces Commander Huseyin Kivrikoglu is also to visit Israel in
January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Weaker Following Asia Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
half a U.S. cent weaker today, weighed down by falls in the
exchange rates of some of its counterparts in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The local currency ended here at 66.31 U.S. cents, down from
66.70 previously. But it was up from a new four-year low of 66.10
during the local session.
</P>
<P>
"Everyone is focusing on what is happening to our northern
neighbors," particularly the currencies of South Korea and
Indonesia, said National Australia Bank foreign exchange trading
manager Mike Eastaway.
</P>
<P>
"No one is taking any notice whatsoever of the local
fundamentals here. The economy is in reasonably good shape,
really."
</P>
<P>
Eastaway said investors were concerned about the impact of the
Asian currency crisis on Australia's trade balance, which is seen
likely to widen further into deficit during 1998.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the immediate outlook for the currency is for it
to edge down below 66 U.S. cents, possibly to as low as 65.80, in
weekend offshore dealings.
</P>
<P>
In Asia today, equities markets in Singapore, the Philippines
and Malaysia were all weaker on worries about the ongoing
financial crisis in the region and its effect on future economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the Australian dollar ended here at 86.21
Japanese yen, from 86.21 previously and at 1.1696 from 1.1900
against the Deutsche mark.  
</P>
</TEXT>
