<HEADLINE> Russian Guards Resume at Unknown Soldiers Tomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Guards at the Unknown Soldiers
Tomb near Moscow's Red Square resumed Friday as instructed by
Russian President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Under a presidential decree, soldiers from the presidential
regiment will stand on guard at the tomb every day from 8 a.m. to
8 p.m. as from Friday, the country's Constitution Day.
</P>
<P>
The watch on the tomb, a monument dedicated to soldiers who
died in World War II, started in January, 1924 on the eve of the
funeral of Vladimir Lenin, the founder of the Soviet state, and
was withdrawn on January 27, 1993.
</P>
<P>
During this period, the presidential regiment also stood guard
at the Post Number One, which was established at the Lenin
Mausoleum on the Red Square.
</P>
<P>
Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin is expected to lay a
wreath at the eternal flames of the tomb Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
