<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll in Traffic Accidents Down in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The number of Japanese killed in
traffic accidents was slightly down this year, with the death toll
reaching the 9,000 mark nine days later than last year.
</P>
<P>
The National Policy Agency (NPA) said in a report today that
the number of traffic accident deaths stood at 9,006 as of
Thursday, down from 9,320 at the same point last year.
</P>
<P>
Japan's traffic accident deaths only record the number of
people who die within 24 hours of an accident.
</P>
<P>
The NPA is hopeful that the toll could stay below the 10,000
mark for the second consecutive year this year. The toll fell
below 10,000 for the first time in nine years last year.
</P>
<P>
Hokkaido in northern Japan has the highest number of traffic
accident deaths with 575, while Tottori and Kochi prefectures,
both in western Japan, have recorded the least traffic accident
deaths with 64 each, the NPA said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
