<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Kazakhstan Cooperate on Oil Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 12 (Xinhua) -- China and Kazakhstan have made
great strides this year in oil-production cooperation, Kuanysh
Sultanov, ambassador of the Republic of Kazakhstan, said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan expects to export 100,000 tons of crude oil to China
by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
China's demand for energy has been fueled by rapid economic
growth, while Kazakhstan is rich in oil reserves. The combination
offers significant opportunities for bilateral cooperation,
Sultanov said.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan invited bids for two oil development projects this
year. China National Petroleum and Gas Corporation was the winning
bidder on both projects.
</P>
<P>
According to an agreement involving 9.5 billion U.S. dollars
and signed by both governments, the two countries will build a
3,000-kilometer oil pipeline between the western part of
Kazakhstan and Karamay in Xinjiang in northwest China. Scheduled
for completion in 2005, the pipeline will transport 20 million
tons of oil from Kazakhstan to China annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
