<HEADLINE> Public Welcome Zambia's Inter-Party Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lusaka, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's Public opinion
welcomed the preliminary meeting held here Tuesday and Wednesday
to map out an agenda for the planned inter-party dialog to settle
the contentious issues like constitution, according to Zambia
Daily Mail.
</P>
<P>
Renowned political commentator Elias Mpondela was quoted as
saying that "I think dialog is always important in resolving
contentious issues. All those people there are Zambians and they
have the capacity to resolve their own issues."
</P>
<P>
He urged everybody to be genuine and said the interests must
be national.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized genuineness and unity of purpose as the two
necessary points for the dialog to be fruitful.
</P>
<P>
"We want to be the mirror of democracy and not the center of
conflict. Maturity must be reflected in the way we resolve
conflicts and so I call on all parties to be serious with
national interests so that the outcome of the talks can reflect
the Zambian culture of peace," Mpondela said.
</P>
<P>
Harriet Chombela, a secretary of a firm, believed the
inter-party talks will help resolve the contentious issues
because they will provide an opportunity for all the parties to
bring out their views.
</P>
<P>
"I think they should go ahead. It is better so that they
listen to each other's views" she said.
</P>
<P>
Chileshe Kamona, also a firm secretary, said the talks are
necessary to avoid finger pointing in future, but they should
have included independent parliament members to be truly
representative.
</P>
<P>
"Looking at the agenda, I think it is necessary to have the
inter-party talks so that no body will be blamed in future," he
said.
</P>
<P>
For Mwando Maswabi, the inter-party talks are a good idea but
he is not sure about the genuineness of the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
He said the government should have lifted the state of
emergency and freed those in detention to provide a conducive
environment for meaningful inter-party talks.
</P>
<P>
Sydney Singoyi, a firm accountant, said the inter-party talks
are necessary but the bottom line should be national interests.
</P>
<P>
Salome Mwanmbazi, a banker, said that the inter-party talks
are absolutely necessary to iron out the areas of conflicts
between the ruling and opposition political parties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
