<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Half Of Shanghai Families Own Their Own Flat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 12 (Xinhua) -- One and a half million
families in urban Shanghai, or about a half of the city's total
households, own their own flats, according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
As individual incomes increase and housing becomes more
commercial, more urbanites are able to buy their own home.
</P>
<P>
Some 650,000 households have bought their government-subsidized
flats since 1994, when Shanghai started to sell
government-subsidized apartments, and more than 800,000 families
have purchased free-market flats.
</P>
<P>
Experts predicted that more local residents will buy their own
houses with the new housing system, sources say. Since the
beginning of the year, real estate developers in Shanghai have
tried various methods to attract more people to buy free-market
flats, and banks have been offering favorable loans that are
long-term and lower interest.
</P>
<P>
In the first nine months, China Construction Bank's Shanghai
Branch issued 3.4 billion yuan in housing loans, exceeding last
year's. As housing reforms increase and the cost of rent versus
the cost of buying changes, it will force more residents to buy
their own flats.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai plans to increase its per capita living space to more
than 10 sq.m. during the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000), and the
city government has started a comfortable housing project which is
aimed at providing housing for with low or moderate-income
families. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
