<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Parties Disqualified from General Election in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Four political parties in
Kenya have been disqualified from the December 29 General
Election for failing to subscribe to the Electoral Code of
Conduct, the Kenya Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The daily newspaper quoted Electoral Commission Chairman
Samuel Kivuitu as saying Thursday that the four parties were
locked out after they failed to sign the mandatory Electoral Code
of Conduct as required by Kenyan law.
</P>
<P>
The Electoral Commission released Thursday a provisional list
of 689 candidates standing in 169 constituencies in the December
29 poll.
</P>
<P>
Out of 210 constituencies in the country, 41 have not sent
their outcome of nominations to the commission by last evening
because of transport problems caused by the torrential rains
during the past several weeks.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Kenya African National Union (KANU) has fielded
parliamentary and civic candidates in all the 169 constituencies,
followed by the Democratic Party of Kenya, 106, Ford-Kenya, 86
and the National Development Party, 83.
</P>
<P>
Of the candidates for the parliamentary race, 36 are women, up
from 18 who vied for the same in the 1992 poll.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 36 women candidates, Wangari Maathai of Liberal
Party of Kenya and Charity Ngilu of Social Democratic Party are
bidding for the presidency of the East African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
