<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 08:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Not to Remove Sentry Posts: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides said today that the Greek Cypriot side had made it clear
it would not remove its sentry posts along the cease-fire line in
a way leaving residential areas unprotected.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure for Luxembourg to attend a European Union
(EU) summit meeting, Clerides made the remarks when commenting on
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's report on the renewal of the
mandate of the Peace Keeping Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP).
</P>
<P>
In a report to the U.N. Security Council Wednesday, the
U.N. chief expressed disappointment that measures to reduce
tension along the Green Line in Cyprus had not been implemented,
and urged the Cypriot government to accept a package of
U.N. proposals agreed to by the Turkish forces.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has proposed to the Greek Cypriot National Guard and
the Turkish forces to extend unmanning of army posts along the
demarcation line, to remove loaded weapons and define a code of
conduct.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said the Greek Cypriot side had made some suggestions
on U.N. proposals on the issue, but he declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
"What the Turks have said was that if we were to accept the
U.N. proposals, they would also accept them," he added.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south and
the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north in 1974 when Turkey invaded
the country and took the northern third of island.
</P>
<P>
A 180-kilometer-long buffer zone across Cyprus separates the
island into two parts. A 1,200 strong U.N. peace-keeping force is
patrolling along the buffer zone, which was set up in 1964 when
conflict between the Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities broke
out.
</P>
<P>
The Luxembourg summit, scheduled for Saturday, will be attended
by members of the European Council, European Commission and
associated countries.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Clerides said that the EU summit was expected to
reiterate that membership negotiations with Cyprus would begin in
April 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
