<HEADLINE> Turkey, Israel, US to Hold Exercises in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Turkey announced today that it
will hold joint naval and air exercises with Israel and the United
States in January.
</P>
<P>
The exercises on January 5-9 is to improve the three navies'
abilities of search and rescue, said a statement issued by the
Turkish General Staff.
</P>
<P>
The navies will exchange experience of emergency operations
through the war games, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The planned maneuvers, which have been postponed for several
times, has triggered sharp criticism from Iran and Arab countries,
which accuse Turkey, a predominantly Islamic country, of betraying
the interests of Muslims.
</P>
<P>
Turkish President Suleyman Demirel left Iran Wednesday before
the concluding of the summit of the Organization of Islamic
Conference. He is believed to avoid being criticized by Islamic
leaders over its military cooperation with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The OIC summit Wednesday passed a resolution, jointly proposed
by Iraq and Syria, indirectedly accusing Ankara of establishing
close military relationship with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel signed several military cooperation
agreements in 1996 in training of armed forces and defense
industry.
</P>
<P>
The two regional powers agreed in principle to produce missiles
during the visit here of Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai on December 8-10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
