<HEADLINE> Turkey Dismisses 58 Pro-Islamic Armymen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's Supreme Military
Council (SMC) today removed 58 armymen from the armed forces due
to their pro-Islamic tendencies, according to radio reports.
</P>
<P>
The SMC decision is final and can not be appealed through the
judicial organs, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, chaired by Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz, discussed
recent developments in Turkey and in the region as well,
especially the fundamentalist threat.
</P>
<P>
The military, which deems itself as a protector of the
country's secular system, has kept a watchful eye on any
infiltration of fundamentalism in its own ranks.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government has adopted a series of measures to curb
the rapidly expanding fundamentalist force in the secular state
since the Islamist Welfare Party (RP) resigned from power last
June.
</P>
<P>
The Constitutional Court is now discussing a case which called
for the closure of the RP on grounds of its anti-secular
activities. 
</P>
