<HEADLINE> Southern Chinese City Solving Housing Problems This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The city of Guangzhou, in
south China's Guangdong Province, expects to solve the housing
problem of people whose average per capita living space is less
than 5 sq.m. by offering another 4,000 apartments for sale.
</P>
<P>
This is part of the city's 11-year drive to ease the housing
shortage, which meant moving some 26,000 households to new homes.
Since 1986 its initial goal was to solve the housing problem for
those whose average capita living space was less than 2 sq.m., and
the number gradually rose to 5 sq.m.
</P>
<P>
In that time, the Guangzhou city government has built five
large-scale residential areas and buildings that were sold at cost
to some 26,000 households, involving 100,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The sources noted that the remaining 3,269 households with
housing problems will be given a choice of 4,000 apartments.
</P>
<P>
Starting next year, the city will give priority to a
"comfortable housing project", which will provide houses for low
and medium-income families, the municipal sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
