<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientist Questions Existence of Northwest China Lake Monster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, December 12 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese scientist has ruled
out the possibility that there is an animal the size of a boat in
a lake in the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Local ethnic minorities have had legends for years about a
mysterious creature in Khanas Lake in the Altay Mountains of
northwestern China, which frequently attacked cattles and people,
and a group of university teachers and students who took a photo
of the animal recently support other reports that say it could be
a kind of "red fish" the size of a 10-meter boat.
</P>
<P>
However, Gao Ailiu, of the Xinjiang Aquatic Science Research
Institute, says that there's never been a red fish as big as a
boat in the region, and explains, "The water of Khanas Lake is
quite cold and there is not enough food to support any animal
weighing over one hundred kilograms."
</P>
<P>
The lake monster has been previously described as a vertebrate
weighing more than a ton, but, "Several research teams, including
one from the Chinese Academy of Sciences, have studied the lake,
but didn't find any such animal," Gao says. He points out that the
monster might be the result of refracted light or an inverted
image in the water. Another possibility is that people thought
that thousands of red fish that gathered to lay eggs were one
fish, when seen from far away.
</P>
<P>
China's most famous lake monster has been one said to be living
in Tianchi Lake in the Changbai Mountains near the border with the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea. People say that it is a
Chinese version of the Loch Ness monster, but many scientists are
skeptical about it.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Technology Helping Create South China's Economic Miracle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Technology has become a
major factor in Guangdong's economic development and is expected
to help the southern Chinese province catch up with other
economies in the country.
</P>
<P>
Government sources say that some 40 percent of the province's
economic production is now from high-tech industries, including
computers, electronics, new materials, and bio-technology.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong is one of China's most prosperous provinces, whose
production accounts for ten percent of the nation's total.
</P>
<P>
The province has attracted people from prestigious universities
like Beijing University and Qinghua University to open research
institutes and companies.
</P>
<P>
Since the early 1990s, more than 100,000 scientists and
technicians have left northern China for Guangdong, where they can
take advantage of more flexible policies to achieve more research
findings. The province has also benefited from the presence of
international giants like NEC, Epson, IBM, and Compaq.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong had 676 high-tech programs last year and has
established nine high-tech development zones since 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
