<HEADLINE> Open Mind Helpful in Finding New Jobs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese laid-off workers
should open their minds to new opportunities for jobs, said a
story in today's People's Daily.
</P>
<P>
After the initial shock and worry, some Shanghai women who were
laid off as textile workers found new opportunities as airline
flight attendants and shop assistants.
</P>
<P>
Other laid-off workers have taken part-time jobs, replacing
those rural women who sought employment in the cities. As they
open their minds, they widen their job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, more than 800,000 laid-off workers in Shanghai have
found jobs, the story said.
</P>
<P>
Yang Xianghua, a laid-off factory worker in Chongqing, created
a private electronics business in 1993. With his thriving business
combining investment, industrial production and scientific
research, Yang recently merged with his former employer.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 25 percent of non-public business runners
come from blue-collar families, 22 percent are former enterprise
officials and 12 percent are technicians. They have found success
in their new jobs, the story said.
</P>
<P>
The country's underdeveloped service sector provides jobs in
such fields as nursing, domestic work and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
An employment fair, organized by Chongqing's trade unions and
concerned agencies, planned to invite applications from laid-off
workers for 3,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
Although nearly 10,000 applicants came to the fair, only 600
signed contracts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Open Mind Helpful in Finding New Jobs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Many workers laid off from state-owned enterprises were
reluctant to take jobs with non-public businesses, accounting for
the most of those at the employment fair.
</P>
<P>
A large luxury guest house in Hangzhou in east China's coastal
Zhejiang Province planned to employ workers from those laid
off. Only about 30 jobless people applied.
</P>
<P>
The country created 11.7 million new jobs in 1996, with 4.4
percent in state-owned enterprises, 23.7 percent with collectives
and nearly 72 percent with private businesses.
</P>
<P>
However, a recent survey shows that 72 percent of those laid
off would first choose state-run enterprises for
re-employment. The state industrial enterprises now have surplus
labor of 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
The 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of China has
formulated the principle of keeping public ownership in a dominant
position and having diverse economic sectors develop alongside.
</P>
<P>
The country will continue adjusting and improving the ownership
structure so as to further release and develop production.
</P>
<P>
Thus, the laid-off workers should change their minds and choose
jobs which are most suitable to themselves, the story said.
</P>
</TEXT>
