<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North China Province Using Fly Ash to Build Expressway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, December 12 (Xinhua) -- North China's Hebei
Province has used 11 million tons of fly ash to construct 72
kilometers of roadbed on the Shijiazhuang-Anyang Expressway.
</P>
<P>
The expressway will be part of the Beijing-Shenzhen
Expressway. At present, construction of the Hebei section is
nearly complete.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, all the fly ash discharged during
past decades in the electricity generation process of thermal
power plants in three cities in Hebei Province -- Shijiazhuang,
Xingtai and Handan -- have been depleted for the roadbed.
</P>
<P>
Local departments have spent an additional 100 million yuan on
the construction of roadbed with fly ash, creating one billion
yuan of economic returns by saving 773 hectares of land from
destruction and by reducing fly ash storage areas by 266.7
hectares.
</P>
<P>
Thermal power generation is prevalent in Hebei Province. The
accumulation of fly ash not only has caused serious environmental
problems, but also has occupied large areas of farmland.
</P>
<P>
Beginning in 1993 the Hebei Provincial Bureau of
Communications, with the full support of relevant state
departments, started using fly ash to build roadbeds for the
Beijing-Shijiazhuang and Shijiazhuang-Taiyuan expressways. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
