<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eighth Beijing Party Congress Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The Eighth Beijing Municipal
Congress of the Communist Party of China (CPC) opened here today.
</P>
<P>
The current congress, attended by 700 delegates, will summarize
the work since the Seventh Congress five years ago and establish
plans for the capital city's development in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
The week-long congress will elect a new leadership for the
Beijing Municipal Party Committee. The congress convenes every
five years.
</P>
<P>
About 10 percent of the 12 million local residents are CPC
members.
</P>
<P>
Jia Qinglin, secretary of the Beijing Municipal Party Committee,
delivered a speech at the congress, on behalf of the Seventh
Beijing Municipal Party Committee.
</P>
<P>
Jia said Beijing's economy sustained increases in the past five
years. By the end of 1997, the capital's gross domestic product
(GDP) is expected to exceed 180 billion yuan (about 21.6 billion
U.S. dollars) at an average annual rate of more than 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
He said the output of the industrial, agricultural and service
sectors will account for 4.7 percent, 41.5 percent and 53.8
percent of the total GDP, respectively. The service sector is
expected to develop rapidly and become a major driving force for
local economic development.
</P>
<P>
Jia also recalled the great changes Beijing has made in the
past five years in economic reform, urban infrastructure,
opening-up, improving local people's living standard, promotion of
cultural and ethical progress, creating a democratic legal system
and building the Party.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Jia stressed further improvement in Beijing's
role as a national political and cultural center.
</P>
<P>
He said while serving the work and life of the local residents,
the capital's various undertakings must serve the work of the
Party, government and army departments, serve the development of
the country's science and technology, education, and cultural
causes, and increase exchanges with foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Looking ahead, Jia said, Beijing citizens will live a fairly
comfortable life by the year 2000, and a socialist market economic
system will initially take shape in the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2010, the capital's economic strength, social
development and local people's living standard will reach the
level of developed capitals around the world, Jia said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
