<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Peso Slides to New Historical Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine currency, the
peso, fell by 4 percent to a new record low of 37.36 pesos to the
U.S. dollar today, triggering a suspension of trading beyond that
level for the rest of the day.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said heavy demand for dollars in the wake of a sharp
plunge in the South Korean currency, the won. pushed the peso down
while the Philippines' Central Bank stopped intervention to make
the peso competitive against other Southeast Asian currencies
which are also faltering.
</P>
<P>
The drop "does not mean that our economy is not good,"
President Fidel Ramos said, adding, "One must not be apprehensive
about what is happening outside. We are affected but we are bound
to recover."
</P>
<P>
The Bankers Association of the Philippines said the peso
reached the third and final volatility band set by the country's
central bank during this morning's trading session.
</P>
<P>
To avoid a further sharp fall of the peso, the central bank
decided that the peso must not trade above or below 4 percent of
Thursday's weighted average of 35.687 pesos per dollar.
</P>
<P>
The peso has devaluated by some 41 percent from 26.4 pesos a
dollar in July to the current level in the financial storm
sweeping much of Asia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
