<HEADLINE> Decline in Number of Job-Related Illnesses in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The incidence of job-related
illnesses in China has declined in recent years, according to a
recent international health symposium in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
China has improved monitoring in the workplace and adopted more
regulations, Liang Youxin, a professor at Shanghai Medical
Sciences University and director of a World Health Organization
(WHO) occupational health center in Shanghai, told the symposium.
</P>
<P>
"China should not ignore health and worker safety during a
period of economic development," said Liang, pointing out that
Chinese records describe occupational hazards and preventive
measures some 1,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The country has started academic institutes and an occupational
health and service network since the mid 1950s, he said, and most
state-funded enterprises have provided emergency medical treatment
for about 40 years.
</P>
<P>
At present, lung diseases account for more than two-thirds of
all job-related illnesses in China, which include chemical
poisoning and skin ailments.
</P>
<P>
The symposium was attended by more than 200 specialists from
the Shanghai Medical Sciences University, and Harvard University
and the Liberty Mutual Group of the United States.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
