<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shippers Want Tanzania Export Levies Reduced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The dredging of the
entrance channel to the Dar es Salaam Harbor will be a waste of
money if the Tanzanian government maintains huge levies on
exports, a shipping official has said.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary General of the Tanzanian Shippers' Council
(TSC), Ulimbakisya Kamola, said in Dar es Salaam Thursday that
"exports should be encouraged instead of being discouraged."
</P>
<P>
The 13.8 billion shillings (about 22 million US dollars)
project, undertaken by the Tanzanian Harbors Authority and being
executed by a Dutch company Ham, involves the widening of
entrance of the Dar es Salaam harbor to accommodate bigger
vessels.
</P>
<P>
Speaking during a preparatory meeting for the eighth TSC
annual general meeting slated for next Tuesday, Kamola said
exports such as coffee are subjected to too many levies and
taxes, according to a report by "The Guardian" today.
</P>
<P>
"The coffee buyer pays levies to the regional, district and
village authorities, while purchasing the crop from the farmers,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
On top of these charges, he said, the government has imposed
export fee of two percent and a stamp duty of 1.2 percent of
export proceeds.
</P>
<P>
Kamola said pre-shipment inspection companies are also paid
1.2 percent as tax assessment and inspection fees.
</P>
<P>
"These payments are unnecessary costs to the shippers," he
said, appealing to the government to readjust rates of the levies
imposed on shippers.
</P>
<P>
He said the government should realize that the captive cargo
in landlocked Zambia and Malawi now have alternative routes to
the sea.
</P>
<P>
"In other words, competition is stiff," he cautioned.
</P>
<P>
The TSC annual meeting, will attract Customs Department and the
National Shipping Agencies Company, banks, railway operators, road
haulers, shipping inspection companies, the Dar es Salaam Handling
Company and clearing and forwarding agents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
