<HEADLINE> China Announces Winner Of Its First Psychology Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Psychology
Society has given its first award to professor Chen Li from
Hangzhou University for his research in psychology.
</P>
<P>
The award is intended primarily for psychologists who have made
a great contribution to and are pre-eminent in the field.
</P>
<P>
The 95-year-old professor is the founder of industrial
psychology in China, and an honorary president of Hangzhou
University in Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
After receiving his doctoral degree at University of London in
1935, Chen was invited to work as a research fellow in what was
then the Central Research Institute and Qinghua University.
</P>
<P>
He helped found the psychology department at Hangzhou
University, which is renowned for its research in the field in
China.
</P>
<P>
His "Introduction to Industrial Psychology", which was
published in 1935, was the first work in the field in
China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Repays Huge Foreign Loans Ahead of Schedule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim announced today that his government has
repaid 12 billion ringgit (about 3.2 billion U.S. dollars) of its
foreign loans ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
If they had not been repaid when the country was enjoying a
good economy, the loans could have reached 25 billion ringgit
(about 6.7 billion U.S. dollars) to 30 billion ringgit (about 8.1
billion dollars) in the wake of the present economic slowdown and
depreciating ringgit, Anwar told reporters after a function in
Subang Jaya near here.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, who is also the country's finance minister, urged the
private sector to heed the federal government's decisions to cut
expenditure by at least 18 percent next year besides an immediate
10 percent across-the-board cutback in both operating and
development expenditures and 8 percent in selected spending.
</P>
<P>
As announced by Anwar earlier, the government's measures to
strengthen economic stability and restore investor confidence also
include a pay cut of 10 percent for ministers and deputy ministers
and 3 percent for officers in super-scale C and above.
</P>
<P>
He encouraged the private sector to trim excessive salaries
paid to professionals and management executives and reminded the
private sector to be prudent in their investments.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said that next year the government may see its earnings
affected due to slower growth in corporate income with the economy
forecast to grow at 4 to 5 percent compared to 8 percent during
the economic boom.
</P>
<P>
He said that because of an anticipated reduction in government
earnings, it would be much better to cut expenditure early.
"Because had we overspent, the country has to be in debt. When we
are in debt... the country would be burdened and so will our
future generation."
</P>
<P>
The minister said it is time to make the necessary adjustments
and take precautionary measures to overcome the economic and
financial turbulence affecting the region.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the need for continuously increasing the
national savings rate, now at 39 percent, as investments stand at
43 to 44 percent, thus creating a gap.
</P>
<P>
The savings-investment gap has been covered by foreign debts
and this has put the country at a disadvantageous position, he
said, adding, "We must have the ability to utilize local fund."
</P>
</TEXT>
