<HEADLINE> Uganda to Increase Farmers' Incomes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Uganda will spend 39 billion
Ugandan Shillings (some 39 million U.S. Dollars) to train farmers
to increase their incomes, The New Vision reported today.
</P>
<P>
Sam Kutesa, the State Minister for Economic Planning, said the
scheme is a part of Uganda Vision 2025 Program under way aimed at
increasing farmers' incomes from 270 U.S. Dollars now to 5,000
U.S. Dollars within 30 years.
</P>
<P>
The emphasis of the scheme will be on the small home
industries that will employ 80 percent of labourers, the state
minister told parliamentarians.
</P>
<P>
Okullo Epak, a parliamentarian from Oyam district, agreed with
the state minister that peasants should be encouraged to launch
their value-adding industries to increase their incomes.
</P>
<P>
Uganda established last month two committees consisting of top
personalities to implement the program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
