<HEADLINE> Guangxi Province Focuses Efforts on Improving Infrastructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIHAI, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Coastal areas in southwest
China's Guangxi Province are expected to catch up with other
coastal provinces and cities in infrastructure construction by
2000.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992 the province has invested more than 17 billion yuan
(2.12 billion U.S. dollars) in infrastructure construction in
three coastal cities -- Beihai, Qinzhou and Fangchenggang.
</P>
<P>
The economy of the three cities, which encompass 20,299 square
kilometers with a population of four million, has developed slowly
in the past.
</P>
<P>
However, the Nanning-Kunming railway now connects the three
cities with other areas of the Southwest and provides the impetus
for their economic development.
</P>
<P>
Local statistics show that the province, with its 1,595
kilometers of coastline, has built three large ports and 76 docks
with an annual handling capacity of 10 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen airlines now link the province with other major
cities of the country, which improves trade conditions.
</P>
<P>
While completing the Qinzhou-Litang railway and the extension
of the Beihai airport, the province also has been busy
constructing the Nanning-Fangchenggang and Qinzhou-Beihai
expressways. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
