<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast China Doing Better at Reducing Unemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Liaoning Province, a leading
industrial base in northeastern China, has found jobs for 1.22
million laid-offs since 1994, according to vice-governor
Guo Tingbiao.
</P>
<P>
The majority of them were laid off their factory jobs as a
result of recent economic changes. At one point, 30 percent of
Liaoning's 10 million industrial workers were jobless.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the provincial government offered jobs for 168,000
jobless people and the number rose to 400,000 this year.
</P>
<P>
Over the next three years, however, the province needs to
provide new jobs for another two million people, so emphasis will
be placed on finding 800,000 jobs in large and medium-sized
state-owned enterprises, Guo said.
</P>
<P>
The province has 926 large and medium-sized enterprises,
accounting for one tenth of China's total.
</P>
<P>
To provide more help for laid-off workers, trade unions across
the province have set up 628 training centers where they can
receive vocational training before looking for new work.
</P>
<P>
Government departments, trade unions, and women's federations
in 14 cities have also formed special groups to co-ordinate job
placement, and 290 job agencies have been established in the
province in recent years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
