<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Auto Market Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese automakers have been
more successful in coordinating sales and production in the past
year, which has had an impact on imports.
</P>
<P>
China's auto market has been growing steadily, according to a
recent national auto industry meeting here.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in the first nine months of this year 1.17
million automobiles were produced in China and 1.14 million were
sold, up 6.9 percent and 8.2 percent from the same period last
year, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Cars were the fastest-growing segment: 368,000 cars were turned
out, and 350,500 were sold in the first three quarters, an
increase of 25.6 percent and 27.2 percent respectively over the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
During this period, the production and sales volume of large
trucks were, respectively, 22,200 and 21,400.
</P>
<P>
Stable growth in China's auto market is expected to carry into
1998. The supply and demand should be around 1.7 million, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
Economists at the meeting based the projection on an expansion
of the taxi business, an increase in individual purchases and a
new government standard to get junk cars off the roads. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
