<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High-tech Bikes to Be Banned in 2000 Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 12 (Xinhua) -- High-technology bicycles
will be banned from championships from January 2000, the
International Cycling Union (UCI) announced in Ipoh, Malaysia, on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to Bernama News Agency, the UCI will issue new
guidelines to all cycling federations to specify the acceptable
bicycle weights, frames and wheel sizes.
</P>
<P>
"If we allow cyclists to use the high technology bicycles, then
it would only be used by the rich countries," said UCI president
Hein Verbruggen.
</P>
<P>
"It is not fair for those who can't afford to buy the expensive
bicycles," Verbruggen added.
</P>
<P>
Verbruggen was in Ipoh for the World Cycling Championship B,
which runs from Friday to December 17.
</P>
<P>
The UCI president said that all cyclists at the Sydney Olympic
Games in 2000 will be required to use "normal" bicycles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
