<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Steps Taken to Protect Animals in Topical Rain Forest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The Xishuangbanna Dai
Autonomous Prefecture of southwest China's Yunan Province has
initiated a ban on hunting to protect wild animals living in
Xishuangbanna, China's biggest tropical rain forest.
</P>
<P>
The area bordering on Myanmar and Laos earned its reputation as
"a kingdom of wildlife" for 427 species of birds, 67 species of
animals and 1,437 kinds of insects. Some 99 endangered species
represented there are put under state protection.
</P>
<P>
To protect the wild animals, the local government has taken
active measures to prohibit poaching, selling, peddling and
processing of wild animals.
</P>
<P>
The hunting ban went into effect in November.
</P>
<P>
Xishuangbanna wildlife officials and local public security
agents have punished poachers according to the law, and
confiscated all weapons taken into the forest.
</P>
<P>
Sources said Xishuangbanna now has one-fourth of the country's
mammal species and one third of the bird species. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Announce Independent Health Policy Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government will
soon announce an independent health policy with a view to raising
the standard of health services in the country, local newspapers
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The government would make a decision, after consulting experts,
on whether to bring foreign doctors to Bangladesh, if there is a
need, newspaper reports quoted Minister of Local Government Rural
Development and Cooperatives Zillur Rahman as saying at a function
in Dhaka Thursday.
</P>
<P>
There has been no independent health policy in Bangladesh since
the country gained independence in 1971, and Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina wants to launch such a policy which would fulfill the
long-cherished desire of the nation, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The present health service system in Bangladesh is not adequate
to meet the needs of its 124.3 million people despite the
government's efforts in this regard.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, Russia to Diversify Bilateral Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 12 (Xinhua)-- India and Russia have decided
to diversify their trade basket to increase their trade volume, a
government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
While maintaining its supply of traditional items through
long-term contracts, the two sides at a meeting here on Thursday
agreed to include new categories to push ahead bilateral trade
from the present level of about 50 billion rupees (1.37 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Lack of buoyancy in bilateral trade was discussed at the fourth
meeting of the Indo-Russian Working Group on Trade and Economic
Cooperation, and the two sides decided to take immediate steps to
improve the current level of trade, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Strengthened banking relations, encouragement of consignment
exports from India and formulation of a new perspective plan would
be among the categories that would be sorted out by the two sides
in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The Indian side is keen to export engineering items to Russia
in addition to traditional items like tobacco, tea and rice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
