<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Breed of Beef Cattle Developed in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Thai researchers said they had
developed a new breed of beef cattle, which can grow to three
times the size of native animals.
</P>
<P>
A fully grown bull of the new breed can weigh up to 1,000 kg,
as against 200 kg of an average native ox, according to
researchers at the Beef Research and Development Center of
Kasetsart University.
</P>
<P>
The new breed, named "Kamphaengsaen" after the name of the
university's campus, is a cross between local and imported breeds,
with 25 percent native, 25 percent brahman and 50 percent
Charolais.
</P>
<P>
The cross-breed cattle can produce much more meat and maintain
the local breed's resistance to disease and resilience to the hot
humid climate.
</P>
<P>
The researchers said that new breed animals are best
slaughtered and consumed at about 500 kg as the meat then tastes
better.
</P>
<P>
The new breed became a hit with ranchers on Thursday when a
five-year-old bull of the new breed weighing 750 kg was on display
at a national agricultural products fair.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Finances Road Improvements in Guatemala </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank approved a
66.7 million U.S. dollar loan to Guatemala Thursday to help
improve the rural road system and strengthen the country's road
capacity.
</P>
<P>
The project aims to improve rural road systems in Guatemala's
zones of extreme poverty which include the provinces of
Heuhuetenango, Quiche, Totonicapan, San Marcos and Alta and Baja
Verapaz.
</P>
<P>
These departments contain about 30 percent of the country's
land areas and about 33 percent of its population.
</P>
<P>
The project will upgrade about 260 kilometers of road links
strategically located on main trade corridors, namely the
Pan-American Highway link between Mexico and Guatemala City, and
in areas with considerable agricultural development potential,
such as San Marcos and Heuhuetenango.
</P>
<P>
The total project cost is about 136.5 million dollars. In
addition to a World Bank loan, the balance will be financed by the
Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund and the Government of Guatemala
with 49.8 million dollars and 20 million dollars
respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
