<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Countries to Face Food Shortages Due to El Nino </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 11 (Xinhua) -- A near-record number of countries
will face food shortages because of crop damage caused by El Nino,
a report of food crops and shortage released by the United Nations
Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) said today.
</P>
<P>
El Nino is expected to wreak havoc in 1998, and its impact has
forced the FAO to add five Central American countries and several
African and Asian nations to its food problem list.
</P>
<P>
This brings the total number of countries with food shortages
to 37. Because of the situation, FAO and World Food Program
directors have approved a 9.4 million U.S. dollar emergency
operation to provide six months of emergency food assistance to
323,000 people in El Salvador, Guatemala, Honduras, Nicaragua and
Panama, the five Central American countries.
</P>
<P>
The weather phenomenon El Nino has damaged cash crops in the
Andes, caused drought in northeastern Brazil and provoked heavy
rains in eastern Africa and some parts of Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former U.S. Cabinet Member Indicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. Housing
Secretary Henry Cisneros was indicted Thursday on 18 felony counts
of conspiracy, obstructing justice and making false statements to
the FBI about payments to a former mistress.
</P>
<P>
He was indicted along with three other people including the
former mistress Linda Jones by Independent Counsel David M.
Barrett in U.S. District Court in the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
Barrett alleged that Cisneros made false statements to FBI
agents during a background investigation when he was nominated to
the Cabinet post in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Cisneros resigned in November 1996 and is now president of
Univision, a Los Angeles-based Spanish television network.
</P>
<P>
The indictment makes Cisneros the second Clinton Cabinet
secretary to be indicted. Former Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy
was charged in August in a 39-count indictment for accepting
illegal gifts and lying to investigators.
</P>
<P>
The indictment alleges that Cisneros, who is married, paid
Linda Jones more than 250,000 U.S. dollars from 1990 through 1993,
and that he conspired with her and the other defendants to mislead
investigators about the payments before and after he became the
secretary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
