<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Government Fails to Pay Back Wages in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The Ukrainian government is
unlikely to make the mammoth wage and pension payments that are in
arrears by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Valery Pustovoitenko pledged to solve the
problem when he assumed the reins of government in July.
</P>
<P>
With only 20 days left in 1997, the total wage and pension
backlog in Ukraine has reached 6.2 billion hryvnas (about 3.2
billion U.S. dollars), one fifth of the 1997 budget revenues,
according to statistics from the National Bank of Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Not only the living standards of ordinary Ukrainians are
affected by the huge debt, but also the political clout of
President Leonid Kuchma and the government as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Political opponents of Kuchma, including leftist forces that
dominate the present parliament, have referred to the wage delays
as evidence that his economic policies are ineffective.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma admitted that not making overdue wage and pension
payments would give the Communist Party a boost in the March 1998
parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
"They have a base -- the pensioners who now receive small
pensions," the president said when speaking to students in the
Zaporozhya region last week. "Pensioners will vote for Communists
because now they live worse than before." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
