<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Walesa Likely to Run in Next Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Poland's former President Lech
Walesa is like to stage a political comeback in the presidential
election due in the fall of the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Polish Press Agency (PPA) reported that Walesa told the
press Wednesday he would not rule out the possibility of running
for president in the future.
</P>
<P>
Walesa has suggested that Poland adopt a presidential
mechanism, but he did not elaborate on the idea. The mechanism, he
said, would be discussed among his party's members and if the
people agree, he would run for office.
</P>
<P>
Walesa returned to his former work unit at the Gdansk Shipyard
and resumed his position as an electrician after he failed in his
bid for re-election for president in 1995.
</P>
<P>
He did not, however, work as an electrician, but was engaged in
political activities. When asked if he would run for president
again on his return to Gdansk, he never gave a definite answer
until recently.
</P>
<P>
He did not think Marian Krzaklewski, the Solidarity Election
Action's (AWS) present chairman, would become his competitor,
Walesa said, because Krzaklewski did not make any new proposals on
presidential goals or mechanisms for the country. Therefore,
Krzaklewski still had a lot to do in order to be a strong
competitor, the PPA reported.
</P>
<P>
However, according to the report, Krzaklewski, who reorganized
the once scattered Solidarity Trade Union and won the
parliamentary election and formed the new cabinet this fall, has
been eyeing the office of president for a long time. Because of
this, he declined the offer to become prime minister. It was
also Krzaklewski that first proposed the Solidarity Trade Union's
next goal, which was to make Aleksander Kwasniewski, the leader of
the Social Democracy of the Republic of Poland, finish his
presidency before it expires.
</P>
<P>
Explaining why he made the choice, Walesa said the goal of the
party founded at his proposal was to avoid a monopoly by the
middle-right wing on the Polish political stage.
</P>
<P>
He said he was afraid the Communist Party would return to power
some day and dissolve the parliament, or the present parliament
expires and the AWS becomes exhausted and loses the opportunity
presented by the election.
</P>
<P>
"I have helped the Solidarity Election Action, I am helping it
and I still will in the future," Walesa said, "but I don't agree
with it because it mixes the tasks of the trade unions with the
ruling of the government, and it will not listen to an old
colleague."
</P>
<P>
Walesa promised he would do everything possible in order to
prevent the communists from resuming power in 20 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
