<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Globalization Brings Opportunities, Challenges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 12 (Xinhua) -- History has never
before witnessed a financial crisis the likes of which is
occurring in Southeast Asia now that has had such an impact on
Wall Street, the financial center of the world.
</P>
<P>
In essence, the crisis is an expression of "globalization" in
the financial field. Economic globalization, which is
exemplified by transnational exchanges of commodities, services
and capital, is ushering a new world into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
With the economy playing an increasingly important role in
international relations after the Cold War, the pace of economic
globalization is accelerating.
</P>
<P>
Developed countries have a growing interest in globalization
because it offers them favorable conditions to realize more
efficient business operations, more appropriate resources
distribution and higher profits. It will also stimulate growth
through expansion of external demand.
</P>
<P>
Globalization can also help developing countries attract more
funds and technologies and to assist in converging their economies
with the international market stream. Therefore, globalization is
also bringing opportunities to many countries.
</P>
<P>
Transnational Corporations (TNCs) stand in the forefront of
globalization. According to United Nations' statistics, the
number of parent firms and their affiliates have surpassed 45,000
and 280,000 respectively. The affiliates' assets have totaled more
than 8.4 trillion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Competition is a prominent feature of the TNCs. In 1996 and
1997, voluminous mergers and acquisitions took place in aviation,
telecommunications, banking and insurance industries in a war to
broaden marketplaces.
</P>
<P>
Expanding at a more rapid pace than global trade, foreign
direct investment (FDI) has played a major role in the
globalization process. The volume of FDI has soared from 166
billion U.S. dollars in the 1980s to 350 billion dollars in 1996 when
global FDI reached a record 3.2 trillion dollars.
</P>
<P>
FDI used to be an activity of the developed nations, but there
has been a new trend for an increase of FDI into developing
countries, which absorbed one third of global FDI inflow in 1996,
the latest figures show.
</P>
<P>
The rapid development of world trade is an important
opportunity for the world community. In the first six years of the
1990s, the growth of world trade was three times that of the world
economy. Every country is taking measures for trade and technology
liberalization in order to bring competition into their production
areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Congressman Convicted of Rape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 12 (Xinhua) -- A city trial judge today
convicted a Philippine congressman of two counts of rape he
allegedly committed against an 11-year-old girl in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Judge Roberto Diokno of the Makati City Regional Trial Court in
Metro Manila said House Representative Romeo Jalosjos was found
guilty of two counts of statutory rape and six counts of acts of
lasciviousness.
</P>
<P>
Judge Diokno, who said the verdict was based on evidence proven
by the prosecution, sentenced Jalosjos to life imprisonment and
ordered him to pay the victim 220,000 pesos (6,300 U.S. dollars)
in moral damages.
</P>
<P>
The judge said his decision could still be contested on appeal
to the higher court by the defense. Meanwhile, he said Jalosjos
was acquitted of four other counts of acts of lasciviousness and
all other charges filed against him earlier.
</P>
<P>
Jalosjos said in the courtroom that he was innocent of the
charges filed by the girl.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Globalization Brings Opportunities, Challenges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The promotion of free trade by developed nations, especially in
the high-tech products and services trade, has added motive force
and served as media to globalization.
</P>
<P>
After succeeding in the signing of agreements on
telecommunications and information technology trade in the World
Trade Organization (WTO), the U.S. has been making efforts to
include more high-tech products into the agreements and to have
more signatories.
</P>
<P>
The developed nations have been asking WTO members to open up
markets for banking, insurance and securities industries.
</P>
<P>
One reason for developed countries to attach importance to
high-tech trade is its role in enhancing productivity and
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
In the U.S., home to one fourth of the world's output,
high-tech industry has become a leading manufacturing sector in
terms of its contribution to the growth of domestic products,
employment and exports.
</P>
<P>
But the opportunities are not evenly shared. One of the topics
that developing countries often talk about in the current session
of the U.N. General Assembly is the negative impact of
globalization on their own countries.
</P>
<P>
Developed nations have become more active in penetrating into
developing countries' financial markets, while the movement of
short-term speculative funds has caused great impact on a host of
countries' markets, such as in the case of Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Because of their relatively low levels of economic and
technical base and lack of competitiveness, most of the developing
countries can not compete for the short or mid-term benefits of
globalization.
</P>
<P>
The least developed nations are prone to marginalization due to
heavy debt burden and aid reduction, and to a widening gap between
them and the wealthier nations.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries are urging their developed partners to get
rid of protectionist and unilateralist practices, to de-link
economic ties with human rights records and market openness, to
stop interfering in other nations' internal affairs through
economic sanctions, and to accord developing countries early
admission to WTO.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries have also called on developed countries to
take concrete steps to improve external conditions of developing
countries and to nurture a "win-win" structure on the basis of
mutual benefit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine's Pension System Needs Overhaul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine's pension system will go
bankrupt if it continues to rely on contributions from only 9
million workers to support 14-million retirees, a Western expert
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
David Snelbecker, an economic adviser from the Harvard
Institute for International Development (HIID), said Ukraine's
"pay-as-you-go" model for supporting retirees, in which each
worker theoretically pays taxes to support the current group of
pensioners, is plagued with problems.
</P>
<P>
"Many workers do not report their true wages and thus pay no
taxes to pension funds," Snelbecker said.
</P>
<P>
The total amount of overdue pension payments to retired persons
has reached 1.4 billion hryvnas (about 740 million U.S. dollars)
by now. The average pension in June was 52 hryvnas (about 25
dollars) per month.
</P>
<P>
The problem will only worsen as Ukraine's retired population
increases, Snelbecker said. According to HIID estimates, over the
next 30 years the ratio of workers to retired citizens will fall
from 3:1 to 2:1.
</P>
<P>
"Only substantial changes will resolve problems that afflict
the system," he said, adding that Ukraine should adopt a fully
funded pension system employing individual retirement accounts.
</P>
<P>
Under such a model, each worker would make mandatory payments
into an account that would provide for his or her own
retirement. This would give workers with an incentive to
participate in the process as well as offering long-term economic
benefits by increasing Ukrainians' savings.
</P>
<P>
Though the problem is urgent enough that it could affect the
outcome of the March 1998 parliamentary elections, Ukrainian
officials consider it is too early to reform the system.
</P>
<P>
"The best time to start reforming is after parliamentary
elections because right now the parliament cares more about their
seats than the reforms," said First Deputy Labor and Social Policy
Minister Svitlana Vegera. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
