<HEADLINE> Drought Death Toll Rises To 657 In Indonesia's Irian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 12 (Xinhua) -- At least 657 people have died
of diseases linked to the prolonged drought in Indonesia's
easternmost province of Irian Jaya, and food shortages still
threaten 150,000 people there, the Antara News Agency reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The secretary of Irian Jaya's disaster task force, Sam Leimena,
said on Thursday that 554 people had died in the districts of
Jayawijaya, Merauke and Puncakjaya.
</P>
<P>
A joint team of the Indonesian Red Cross and the International
Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) said last month that another 103
people had died of drought-related afflictions since October in
Mimika district.
</P>
<P>
The drought that began in May has wiped out local yam crops on
which many of Irian Jaya's tribes are highly dependent.
</P>
<P>
Wells have dried up, prompting local people to drink
contaminated water, which has led to outbreaks of cholera. Fires
have destroyed plants from which many tribes make their clothes.
</P>
<P>
State Minister of National Development planning Ginandjar
Kartasasmita said on Thursday that the government had spent 200
billion rupiah (46 million U.S. dollars) on relief operations to
drought-hit Irian Jaya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
