<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People's Daily Editorial on Creating New Economic Situation (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The People's Daily, China's
leading newspaper, carried an editorial today hailing the Central
Economic Conference held by the Central Committee of the Communist
Party of China (CPC) and the State Council, which ended Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The editorial, titled "Blazing a new trail for reform, opening
up and economic development," said that the conference is of
great importance for making new achievements in reform, opening up
and the socialist modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
The conference summarized the country's economic performance
this year and has set the guiding principles, overall requirements
and key points for economic development in the coming year, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
China has succeeded in making progress amid stability for its
economic development and continuing an appropriately rapid growth,
with price increase rate falling lower and major economic targets
basically meeting the projected aims of the national
macro-economic adjustments, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, China has made progress in promoting market-oriented
activities, scored positive and new changes in economic structural
adjustments, considerably expanded its foreign economic and
technological exchanges, and further consolidated and developed
the positive start of the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000), the
editorial said.
</P>
<P>
What is especially worth noting is that China has basically
escaped from a supply shortage situation in the past year, and
formed a buyers' market for major means of production and consumer
goods, indicating a historic shift of strategic significance, the
paper stressed.
</P>
<P>
However, the whole Party and the people should remain
sober-minded because some outstanding contradictions and problems
in national economic operations still exist.
</P>
<P>
The main contradictions and problems are: a number of
state-owned and township enterprises are running in the red; the
ranks of laid-off workers are rising and some workers face
employment difficulties; redundant construction remains
commonplace; and the fragile foundation of agriculture has not
completely changed yet.
</P>
<P>
1998 will be the first year for tasks established at the CPC's
15th National Congress. China will continue to promote a
fundamental shift in its economic restructuring and growth,
reinforce the status of agriculture as an economic base, speed up
the reform of the state-owned sector, step up efforts to
restructure the economy, improve macro-economic controls, open
wider to the outside world in a bid to maintain economic
development and achieve comprehensive social progress, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Of the six major tasks for next year's economic work, the
conference gave top priority to reforming state
enterprises. Localities have been urged to implement every target
adopted at the conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
