<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economy in CIS Countries Improves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The economy in the Commonwealth
of Independent States (CIS) is showing signs of recovery. The
average gross domestic product (GDP) grew 0.3 percent in the first
ten months of this year.
</P>
<P>
A report released Thursday by the CIS's inter-state statistics
committee said CIS countries gained the 0.3 percent growth rate
following a GDP decline of 5.5 percent in the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
Among the 11 member states, nine recorded a GDP growth ranging
from 0.3 percent to 11.8 percent, while Ukraine and Moldova saw
their GDP fall about 4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The industrial production of the CIS countries this year grew
2.3 percent in contrast with the 3.5 percent decrease in the same
period last year, it said.
</P>
<P>
Kyrgyzstan, Belarus and Georgia achieved an increase of 49.2
percent, 16.4 percent and 10.9 percent in industrial output
respectively. Ukraine, Moldova and Tajikistan have yet to reverse
the economic downslide. Their industries are reporting a decline
of 2.1 percent to 7 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the CIS states and non-CIS countries this year
rose 1 percent, but among the CIS states, it fell 8.7 percent, the
report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
