<HEADLINE> Beijing Newspaper Highlights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The annual Central Economic Conference, held in Beijing
between December 9-11, proposed to promote thorough reforms
related to China's economic system restructuring and growth
patterns, accelerate state enterprise reform, strengthen and
improve macroeconomic controls and open further to the outside
world.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin gave a keynote address concerning the
current international and domestic situation. Premier Li Peng,
Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji and other Party and state leaders Qiao
Shi, Liu Huaqing, Hu Jintao, Wei Jianxing and Li Lanqing also
attended the conference.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin yesterday listened to the
first progress report by Tung Chee-hwa, chief executive of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that in the past five months the Hong Kong SAR
government led by Tung has make remarkable achievements through
hard work. Facts show that Hong Kong people are capable of running
their own affairs and the SAR has a good beginning, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- A People's Daily editorial on the Central Economic
Conference was frontpaged in the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The leadership of the Communist Party of China Central
Committee with Jiang Zemin as the core and the guidance of Deng
Xiaoping Theory and the basic line of the Party have enabled China
to score notable achievements in reform, opening and socialist
modernization drive, the editorial said.
</P>
<P>
China's economy has registered appropriately rapid growth with
low-level price rises in 1997. The market played an increasingly
important role in economic operations and the allocation of
resources. In addition, overall economic structural adjustments
showed signs of positive change, it added.
</P>
<P>
-- Li Ruihuan, chairman of the National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference, called
yesterday for efforts to strengthen Sino-New Zealand bilateral
ties.
</P>
<P>
Li hailed the wide-ranging development of Sino-New Zealand
relations over the past 25 years. He noted that countries should
equitably and fairly handle the ties between their respective
interests and seek common development on the basis of equality,
mutual benefit, complementarity and reciprocity.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Chi Haotian, vice-chairman of China's Central Military
Commission and minister of national defense, met yesterday in
Beijing with Joseph Prueher, command-in-chief of the US Pacific
Command.
</P>
<P>
Chi said Sino-US relations have made great strides over the
past year. He also said that the Chinese side is ready to join
with the US to remove all obstacles to achieving the goal of
increasing understanding, expanding common ground and developing
co-operation.
</P>
<P>
-- China supports United Nations' activities celebrating the
50th anniversary next year of the signature of the United Nations
Universal Declaration of Human Rights, Foreign Ministry spokesman
Tang Guoqiang said yesterday in Beijing. 
