<HEADLINE> Shandong Province Opens Another Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 12 (Xinhua) -- The Laizhou Port on the
northern part of China's Shandong Peninsula was opened, making it
the 10th in Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
The port owns a 10,000-ton berth and three 3,000-ton berths,
and schedules an annual handling capacity of 2.4 million tons. It
is expected to handle 1.2 million tons of cargo this year,
according to Zhang Xinqi, mayor of the city of Laizhou.
</P>
<P>
Trail operation of the port started 1996, mainly handling
cargo of salt, marble, talcum, sand and aquatic products.
</P>
<P>
Among the 10 opened ports in the province, the Qingdao Port is
the country's second largest container port. Its total
transporting volume will top 70 million tons this year.
</P>
<P>
An official from the provincial government said the 10 ports
with 30 international navigation lines to nearly 200 harbors
overseas, have a combined annual capacity of 150 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Ports in Shandong have played a key role in imports and exports
of petroleum, coal, cement, iron ore, building material, cereal
and edible oil in north China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
