<HEADLINE> Chinese Dominance Over Diving Shaken </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 12 (Xinhua) -- China faces an uphill battle
to defend its reputation as the world top diving power in the
Eighth World Swimming Championships in January, a Chinese swimming
official said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"China is no longer as strong as before since three-time
women's Olympic gold medalist Fu Mingxia has retired and Olympic
springboard champion Xiong Ni is well past his prime," said Guo
Qinglong, vice chairman of the Chinese Swimming Association.
</P>
<P>
The world championships, which will be held for January 8-18 in
Perth, Australia, will be Xiong's last outing before he calls it
quits. Xiong said he wanted to wrap up his career with a world
title but the difficulty was enormous.
</P>
<P>
Guo predicted the Chinese divers would meet strong challenges
from Russia, Canada, the United States, Germany and Mexico,
tipping Russian Dimitry Sautin as the top threat to the Chinese
men.
</P>
<P>
Saudin won the men's platform title in the Atlanta Olympics in
absence of defending champion Sun Shuwei of China, who has been
sidelined with injuries and will sit out the Perth championships.
</P>
<P>
In the annual World Cup last September, Saudin once again ruled
the roost in the platform event, edging Chinese youngster Xu Hao
out of the top two.
</P>
<P>
China bagged six gold medals in the World Cup but none of them
was Olympic event.
</P>
<P>
"The World Cup sounded an alarm to the Chinese divers," Guo
said.
</P>
<P>
The Perth-bound Chinese diving team is comprised of 10 men
divers and as many women. Xiong Ni and Yu Zhuocheng, springboard
runner-up in the Atlanta Games, and Wang Rui, heir apparent to Fu
Mingxia and two-time National Games champion in platform, are the
brightest stars on the squad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
