<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Outlines Plan to Explore Oil Fields in Bohai Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Two separate oil fields in the
central part of the Bohai Sea will be explored simultaneously, and
the oil obtained will be piped inland through the port of Tangshan
in north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
According to a recently drafted plan, the two oil fields --
Qinhuangdao 32-6 Oil Field and Nanbao 35-2 Oil Field -- will
produce four million tons of crude oil a year when operational.
</P>
<P>
Qinhuangdao oil field, with 170 million tons of verified geological
oil reserves, is 100 kilometers east of Tanggu in Tianjin.
The field was discovered by China Offshore Oil Corporation's Bohai
Company in June of 1995. Eleven wells have been drilled in the oil
field.
</P>
<P>
Nanbao, discovered recently by the Bohai Company, lies 20
kilometers south of Tangshan. Four test wells have been drilled
and geological reserves of 70 million tons have been
identified. Nanbao's reserves have been estimated at 110 million
tons.
</P>
<P>
The distance between the two oil fields is just 20 kilometers,
making it possible for their joint development in a
70-square-kilometer oil-bearing area in the central Bohai Sea.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the plan, seven standard platforms will be
erected in the two oil fields; two pipelines will be laid at the
seabed to transport oil inland; and terminals will be built in
Jingtang Port. Requisition of 650 meters of coastline will be made
for building oil transport berths. The entire construction will
cost 7.29 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The Qinhuangdao field is expected to begin production in 2003
and Nanbao one year later. By 2004, the two fields should be able
to produce four million tons of oil a year, according to local
sources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Looking for Ways To Keep China's Yellow River From Drying Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, December 12 (Xinhua) -- China's Shandong Province has
been trying hard to find ways to solve its problem with the Yellow
River, which is drying up.
</P>
<P>
The province has sent researchers to Yellow River areas and has
discussed ways to solve its problem with experts.
</P>
<P>
Yellow River, China's second longest, is a major source of
water for Shandong, where 25 counties and cities depend on it for
drinking and irrigating 1.867 million hectares of farmland, and
for industrial use in some cities.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the problem has gotten more serious. This
year, the river has been dry for more than 200 days, causing
problems for agriculture, industry, people, and livestock along
both banks of the river.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the present chaotic system is in drastic need
of reform and needs more unified leadership, planning, and
administration of water resource use, and the price of water needs
to be raised to increase efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Experts are also asking for quick implementation of the water
diversion plan to move water from the Yangtze River to the Yellow
River to help solve the water shortage problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Xiang Sets Three Women's 70kg World Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHIANG MAI, Northern Thailand, December 11 (Xinhua) -- China's
strongwoman Xiang Fenglan broke all the three world records in the
women's 70-kilogram category at the 11th Weightlifting World
Championships here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Xiang snatched 105.5 kilograms in her second attempt, rewriting
the record of 105.0 kgs set by compatriot Yu Wenyu in Lahti,
Finland, in August this year.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old Chinese girl produced a new world record of
130.5 kgs in the clean and jerk contest, as she successfully
jerked the bar 0.5 kg heavier than the record set by China's Qu
Lihua in Yangzhou, China in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
Xiang's success in the snatch and the clean and jerk bringing
her the third world record with a total of 235.0 kgs, eclipsing
the previous record of 232.5 created by Yu in Lahti in August.
</P>
<P>
Xiang was the first weightlifter who broke all the three world
records and bugged the three gold medals in a single category
during the Championships started on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Hungarian Ilona Danko and Huang Hsi-Li from Chinese Taipei took
the snatch silver and the bronze with 100.0 kgs and 97.5 kgs,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The second place in clean and jerk went to Russian Irina
Kasimova in 122.5 kgs and in the third spot was Huang with 120.0
kgs.
</P>
<P>
Huang and Irina also staged the runner-up and the third in the
total with 217.5 kgs and 215.0 kgs.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 83kg-class contest, China's Zhang Yong captured
the gold medal in the clean and jerk with 207.5 kgs, but failed in
his three attempts in the snatch.
</P>
<P>
Poland's Cofalik Andrzej took the snatch title and the total
gold with 172.5 kgs and 380.0 kgs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
