<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Brief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The following economic
news briefs are from Latin American countries within the past few
days:
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Sinderar, the biggest Argentine steel-making
firm, will invest 800 million U.S. dollars to double its capacity
by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
The firm controls 80 percent of the steel plate market in
Argentina. It is estimated that the domestic steel market will
grow 9-10 percent in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
The investment is expected to increase capacity to nearly four
million tons.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- The Chilean trade deficit amounted to about 500
million dollars from January 1 to November 15 of this year.
</P>
<P>
The deficit was a result of more than 15 billion dollars of
exports and 15.5 billion dollars of imports.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The Central Bank of Uruguay reserves, valued at
market prices, has been reduced by 140 million dollars so far this
year.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-two percent of the losses were a result of the drop in
the price of gold. Uruguay has not sold gold since August 1993.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- The 1997 direct foreign investments in Venezuela
reached 800 million dollars, a 150 percent increase over last year.
</P>
<P>
Investments Promotion National Council statistics show that the
manufacturing sector receives most of the capital, followed by the
services sector, oil, mines and agri-business.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- The Inter-American Development Bank (IADB)
approved a 100-million-dollar loan to improve the Colombian
provincial road network.
</P>
<P>
The project aims to increase the country's planning capacity,
as well as to modernize and make more efficient the roads under
provincial responsibility.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- The Costa Rican economy is expected to increase 3
percent this year and inflation will be below 12 percent, Finance
Minister Francisco de Paula Gutierrez said.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- The Copa Panamanian airline plans to spend 480
million dollars to buy 16 new airliners to increase its presence
in the Latin American market.
</P>
<P>
Copa Chairman Pedro Heilbron said the company is negotiating
with the European Airbus consortium and expects to receive the
first aircraft in 1999.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazilian instant coffee exports earned 358.5
million dollars this year, a 10.6 percent drop over last year.
</P>
<P>
The export of instant coffee will be reduced to 9.3 percent to
52,600 tons this year compared with last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
