<HEADLINE> Chinese Swimmers Can Hardly Peak in Perth Worlds, Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese swimmers can hardly
peak again in January's World Swimming Championships after their
shining performance in the National Games last October.
</P>
<P>
"They can hardly peak again in just three months," said Yuan
Jiawei, general secretary of the Chinese Swimming Association.
</P>
<P>
"I don't expect them to put up very good results in the world
championships," added Yuan, who came short of saying how many gold
medals the Chinese aimed for in the quadrennial event to be held
for January 8-18 in Perth, Australia.
</P>
<P>
Two world records and 10 world best times for the year were
produced in the pool at the Eighth Chinese National Games in
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Chen Yan, 16, swam a new world record clocking of 4:34.79 in
the women's 400m individual medley and Wu Yanyan, 19, broke the
world mark of the women's 200m individual medley in 2:09.72.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Weimin, vice minister of the Chinese Physical Culture and
Sports Commission, later slapped at the near-sightedness of
provincial sports officials, who urged their athletes to peak in
the national events instead of encouraging them to reserve the
best for big meetings.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese athletes should compete in their best in international
and world events instead of concentrating on internal strife," the
vice minister said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese world championships delegation included eight men
and 16 women swimmers.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Chengji, who finished fourth in both men's 50m freestyle
and 100m butterfly in the Atlanta Olympic Games, tops the men's
squad, while the women's team is led by Olympic champion Le Jingyi
and world record holders Chen Yan and Wu Yanyan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
