<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Development Zones Boosted in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hunan
Province has made great strides in the construction of development
zones to boost the local economy.
</P>
<P>
As an inland province, Hunan needs to pay close attention to
the construction of development zones to shorten the economic gap
with coastal areas, said a provincial official.
</P>
<P>
The province has established 60 development zones since 1988,
including two state-grade zones and 29 province-grade zones.
</P>
<P>
While providing preferential policies on taxes, loans and land,
the province has invested more than 13 billion yuan (1.62 billion
U.S. dollars) in infrastructure construction.
</P>
<P>
More than 890 joint ventures, cooperative enterprises and
wholly overseas-funded companies have been built in these
development zones with a foreign investment of 1.3 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 alone, the development zones absorbed more than 300
million U.S. dollars in foreign funds, accounting for 45 percent
of the province's total.
</P>
<P>
Also important for the development zones are efficient systems
of law, accounting, finance and insurance, said a governmental
official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, December 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG -- Turkey has suffered another setback in its
efforts to join the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister of Luxembourg Jean Claude Juncker, who is
hosting the EU summit beginning Friday, said Turkey would not join
a new conference which would group all countries pursuing EU
membership. (Turkey-EU Entry Setback)
</P>
<P>
