<HEADLINE> More Cliff Inscriptions to Be Added to Mount Jiuhua </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, December 12 (Xinhua) -- East China's Anhui Province
plans to carve more inscriptions onto the cliffs of Jiuhua
Mountain, a famous tourist attraction and sacred place of Buddhism
in China.
</P>
<P>
Only 40 inscriptions from its 2,000-year development remain for
tourists to view, considered an inadequate number for such a
sacred place.
</P>
<P>
The local government plans to carve a group of about 100
inscriptions on the cliffs, which will include the writing of
celebrities, Chinese calligraphers and Buddhists.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the project goes smoothly, the Jiuhua Mountain
Administration Office has set up a special group to supervise the
construction.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to be completed by the end of
1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
