<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Standardizing Region's Ethnic Languages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region has made considerable efforts to
standardize the languages of local ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
The regional government has passed a series of regulations and
laws to develop and improve ethnic languages since the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, the region has published groups of regulations and
dictionaries of standard phonetics and words in such ethnic
languages as Uygur, Kazak, Kirgiz and Sibo.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, local language experts have conducted field
research projects. They have standardized more than 80,000 ethnic
language terms in the natural and social sciences.
</P>
<P>
In the last seven years, Xinjiang has developed three high-tech
projects which use computers to deal with ethnic languages.
</P>
<P>
There are 47 ethnic groups living in Xinjiang, seven of whom
have their own languages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
