<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Chip Sales Hit Year-Long High in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Global semiconductor sales
reached 11.99 billion U.S. dollars in October, the month of the
highest sales this year, the U.S. Semiconductor Industry
Association (SIA) announced today.
</P>
<P>
Sales in Europe at 2.53 billion dollars were a 6.2 percent rise
over September and a 13.3 jump over the same period in 1996, the
SIA said in its monthly report issued from San Jose, California.
</P>
<P>
Sales in Europe showed the most dramatic month-to-month gains
while sales in the U.S. and Asia Pacific continued to show the
most dramatic year-to-year growth, it said.
</P>
<P>
Sales in the U.S. market rose to 3.98 billion dollars,
representing a 1 percent upturn over September and a 15.4 percent
hike over October 1996.
</P>
<P>
October sales reached 2.73 billion dollars in Asia Pacific, a
1.7 percent increase from September and 21.4 percent growth from
October 1996.
</P>
<P>
In October, depreciation of yen caused Japan's sales to drop
2.5 percent from September to 2.74 billion dollars, which was also
a 0.8 percent decline from October 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Asia Pacific market remains strong despite the recent
currency crisis in South Korea and other Asian countries and over
the long term, demand for semiconductor products is forecast to
continue expanding in all markets, said an official of the SIA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
