<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exports to Grow 12.4 Pct in Latin America in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Latin American exports are
expected to shoot up by 12.4 percent in 1997, according to
preliminary estimates to be published soon by the Integration and
Regional Programs Department of the Inter-American Development
Bank (IDB).
</P>
<P>
The increase in trade for the Western Hemisphere, as well as
for the total of subregional trade groups, is also expected to be
in the double digits, surpassing the rate of trade growth for the
world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Total trade in the hemisphere is expected to be around 1.2
trillion U.S. dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
Overall exports of the Western Hemisphere are expected to
increase by 10 percent this year. Similar increases are also
expected for exports of the three major subregional trade
agreements, the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA), which
will be 10.1 percent, Mercosur 9.8 percent and the Andean
Community 10.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Exports by the Group of Three which consists of Colombia,
Mexico and Venezuela are expected to grow by 14.2 percent, and by
the Central American Common Market 15.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary estimates show that countries are continuing to
deepen their trade ties among the members of the same subregional
integration agreement. All the subregional integration agreements
are increasing their intrasubregional trade at a greater rate than
total trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
