<HEADLINE> World Bank Assists Poverty Reduction in Georgia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today
approved a 20 million U.S. dollar equivalent credit to Georgia as
the social investment fund to help reduce poverty and foster
development of the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The project aims to support the poor among the Georgian
population by improving their access to basic social and economic
services through the rehabilitation of the existing
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
It will also mobilize public and private resources for
small-scale investments or "microprojects" in approximately 400
communities. Based on results of the project's pilot phase, water
supply, irrigation, roads and school microprojects are expected to
be the most common type of investment.
</P>
<P>
The credit, which has a maturity of 35 years, including a
10-year grace period, will be channeled through the International
Development Association (IDA), the World Bank's concessionary
lending arm for developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Since joining the Bank in 1992 and the IDA in 1993, the World
Bank/IDA commitments to Georgia total some 366 million dollars for
14 projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
