<HEADLINE> Reno Offers to Answer More Campaign Finance Questions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Attorney General Janet
Reno today offered to answer more campaign finance questions from
a committee of the U.S. House of Representatives, but remained
reluctant to provide an edited version of a dissenting memo from
the FBI director.
</P>
<P>
Reno told her weekly news conference that she wanted to do
everything she can to "honor the oversight function (of Congress),
while at the same time making sure that nothing is done that would
impair or undercut my responsibility for conducting a full and
vigorous investigation."
</P>
<P>
Reno and FBI Director Louis J. Freeh refused during hearings
Tuesday and Wednesday to comply with a subpoena from the House
Government Reform and Oversight Committee for Freeh's November 25
memo recommending Reno seek appointment of an independent counsel
to investigate fund-raising phone calls, which she rejected.
</P>
<P>
Some Congressional Republicans threatened to hold her and Freeh
in contempt.
</P>
<P>
Reno said she had advised the panel that "after the hearing,
we'd sit down and see what we could work out." She said her staff
was in touch with the committee.
</P>
<P>
She said she remained determined "to make sure that people feel
that they can fully and frankly discuss issues with me without it
becoming public and appearing in congressional committees. It's
not the way to conduct an investigation." 
</P>
</TEXT>
