<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Plane Lands Itself After Pilot Blacks Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 11 (Xinhua) -- A Kansas small plane
automatically flew out of gas and landed safely in a field after
the pilot blacked out while flying his plane because of gas
poisoning, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Rob Frayser, 47, was apparently overcome by carbon monoxide
from a leaking exhaust system after flying about 161 kilometers
from his home in Hoisington in central Kansas to Missouri
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Because the plane was set on an auto-pilot flying, it continued
flying for 560 kilometers more until the fuel ran out, then
glided down to a near perfect landing in a snow-covered Missouri
hay field.
</P>
<P>
The plane skidded about 150 meters without the wings ever
touching the ground, then crashed into a row of trees at the end
of the field.
</P>
<P>
"I woke up totally disoriented and didn't know if I was in the
air or on the ground or what," he said. He said the first reaction
he did was to switch the fuel tanks, lower the gear and add power,
but nothing seemed to help.
</P>
<P>
"Finally I saw the trees around me, so I opened the door and
got out," he said.
</P>
<P>
He walked away with only a broken arm, cuts and bruises and was
back at work Tuesday at the Hoisington Medical Center, where he
practices osteopathic medicine.
</P>
<P>
National Transportation Safety Board investigator Jim Silliman
said, "If it hadn't run out of gas when it did, he would have died
from the carbon monoxide."
</P>
<P>
Silliman said the snow probably helped the landing. "Everything
went in his favor. All the little things added up," he said. "He's
more than lucky." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Faces Another EU Setback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, December 11 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has suffered another
setback in its efforts to join the European Union (EU), it was
learned here today.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister of Luxembourg, Jean Claude Juncker, who is
hosting the EU summit beginning tomorrow, said Turkey would not
join a new conference which would group all countries pursuing EU
membership, according to BBC World Service.
</P>
<P>
Juncker said that all other applicants to the Union would be
told they could start entry talks early next year, but he said
that Turkey had to wait.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister explained that Turkey had to fulfil certain
obligations in the first place, including an improvement in its
human right record, good neighborly relationship with Greece and a
readiness to allow EU entry negotiations with Cyprus to go ahead.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the EU's executive body, recommended
in July that entry talks be started first early next year with
Poland, Hungary, the Czech Republic, Estonia, Slovenia and Cyprus,
applicants considered advanced in political and economic terms.
</P>
<P>
But some EU member countries insist that the EU should begin
talks at the same time with the other five applicants -- Bulgaria,
Romania, Latvia, Lithuania and Slovakia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
