<HEADLINE> China to Receive Environmental Textbooks from U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 11 (Xinhua) -- China will receive
environmental education textbooks from a U.S. non-governmental
organization called Global Communications for Conservation (GCC).
</P>
<P>
This is stipulated by an agreement signed here today between
GCC and China's State Science and Technology Commission (SSTC).
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, the first American textbooks to be
translated and distributed to schools and teachers in China will be
the Environmental Action Series, such as energy conservation,
habitat and biodiversity and waste reduction.
</P>
<P>
Texts, geared for both college students and elementary
school-aged children, will be translated while environmental
education programs for government official will also be developed.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first instance of such cooperation between China
and the U.S. private sector and we are pleased to be launching such
an historic joint venture," said Chairman of GCC Laura Utley.
</P>
<P>
Witnessing the signing of the agreement was Vice Minister of
SSTC Deng Nan who received 1997 Safari Planet Earth Award from GCC
last night.
</P>
<P>
The program is important to China's sustainable development,
and it proves that there are many fields that China and the United
States can cooperate in, said Deng Nan.
</P>
<P>
Since the Earth Summit at Rio de Janeiro in 1992, China has
taken steps to educate the public on the benefits of conservation
and sustainability, the responsibility towards the environment,
the accountability to the future generations and the need for
cooperative global action, Deng Nan added.
</P>
<P>
The New York-based GCC was established in 1989 to initiate
conservation and environmental education programs in the U.S. and
elsewhere. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
