<DOCNO> XIE19971212.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Airports to Be Too Crowed Next Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. airports will be
too crowded and the skies will be more dangerous in the next
century if no dramatic measures are taken, warned a government
commission in a study released today.
</P>
<P>
The study conducted by the National Civil Aviation Review
Commission warned of a "looming disaster" of aviation gridlock
that could set in soon after the year 2000 and damage the U.S.
economy.
</P>
<P>
"We'll have packed terminals, packed planes, packed skies and
constant delays," said the commission chairman, Norman Mineta.
</P>
<P>
Without effective measures, the study warned, the number of
major crashes in the United States will nearly double by the year
2010.
</P>
<P>
"Like old bridges and crowded highways, congested airports and
airways supported by outdated equipment can be less safe," the
commission said. "A system straining at the seams of capacity is
one that is also straining to be safe."
</P>
<P>
The 21-member panel urged the Congress and the White House to
make reforms on the management of the Federal Aviation
Administration (FAA).
</P>
<P>
The commission, which consists of representatives from
different parts of the aviation industry and independent public
members, proposed the FAA improve the air-traffic control system
and airports to accommodate the rising air traffic early next
century.
</P>
<P>
The panel suggested air-traffic control costs be funded through
user fees paid by the airlines and others, and federal spending on
airport improvements be increased by 300 million U.S. dollars a
year over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
The commission also recommended the FAA and the aviation
industry develop a "comprehensive" strategy to improve flight
safety. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
