<HEADLINE> US Hints Possible Arrest of Karadzic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
hinted that the Stabilization Force (SFOR) in Bosnia may arrest
former Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic in the next few
months.
</P>
<P>
"We, the United States... do not rule out any options," said
State Department spokesman James Foley.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed that Karadzic should turn himself in to the
international tribunal in the Hague.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the spokesman also urged the Bosnian Serb government
to turn Karadzic over to the tribunal for a trial, claiming the
governments "where these indicted war criminals reside are
committed, obligated" to do so.
</P>
<P>
The NATO-led force in Bosnian is due to pull out of Bosnia in
June next year and a smaller force will follow up.
</P>
<P>
"SFOR has a mandate to arrest war criminals in the -- as SFOR
goes about performing its primary tasks if the tactical situation
permits," Foley said.
</P>
<P>
"It's not something that we can talk about in detail in terms
of what might or might not happen in the future," he added.
</P>
<P>
Karadzic, who led the Bosnian Serbs for independence from a
Muslim-dominated Bosnian government two years ago, was singled out
and indicted by the West as a war criminal during the three-party
civil war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
