<HEADLINE> U.S. Declines Comment on Jerusalem Census Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 11 (Xinhua) -- The United States on
Thursday declined to make any comment on recent dispute between
Israel and the Palestinians over census in East Jerusalem,
saying it was because Jerusalem is the most sensitive issue.
</P>
<P>
The dispute occurred when the Palestinian Authority sought to
take a census of Palestinians living in East Jerusalem on
Wednesday. But the Israeli parliament rushed to pass a law on the
same day to ban the census.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Foley, dodging a reporter's
question about Washington's reaction to the dispute, said the
United States could only repeat its calls for refrain from both
sides concerning the status of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"Jerusalem is really the most sensitive issue, and it's one
that we believe that the parties have agreed to treat when they
get to the permanent status negotiations," Foley said.
</P>
<P>
"We, the United States, have repeatedly asked both sides to
refrain from unilateral actions which might be considered
provocative by the other side, and which might predetermine the
outcome of issues that need to be decided in permanent status
negotiations," he added.
</P>
<P>
Israel captured East Jerusalem from Jordan in the 1967 Middle
East War, and by reuniting the city declared it the eternal
capital. But the international community including the United
States have refused to recognize Israel's declaration.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian Authority intends to establish a state with
East Jerusalem as its capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
